INSERT INTO `instructor` VALUES (1,'Sharon','Radcliff','Business Librarian','Saint Mary\'s College of California','sradclif@stmarys-ca.edu','<p>Sharon Radcliff (MLIS, MA) has been the business librarian at Saint Mary\'s College in Moraga, California, for the past eight years. She has also taught English reading, writing, and information literacy at various colleges for the past several years.</p>\r\n','Sharon Radcliff (MLIS, MA) has been the business librarian at Saint Mary\'s College in Moraga, California for the past eight years. She has also taught English reading, writing and information literacy at various colleges, for the past several years.\r\n',''),(2,'Sarah','Smith','Instructor','','olfactory8@gmail.com','<p>Sarah Smith has been teaching letterpress printing, bookbinding, and printmaking for ten years at Montserrat College of Art, where she helped create a letterpress printing studio and BFA concentration in Book Arts.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>She is a founding member of Imposition Press,which is also at Montserrat. She also teaches letterpress at Mass Art and book arts workshops for Simmons Graduate Studies in Library Science. While teaching, Sarah worked for the past 15 years as a rare book conservator at the Northeast Document Conservation Center, in Andover MA and before that at the Conservation Center for Art and Historic Artifacts in Philadelphia, PA. Previous to teaching at Montserrat, Sarah taught book arts at Maryland Institute College of Art.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Her work can be found in collections and with booksellers such as Vamp and Tramp Booksellers in Alabama; Printed Matter in NYC; The Banff Centre in Canada; The Kohler Art Library, University of Wisconsin, Boston Public Library; The Fogg Art Museum at Harvard University; The Bancroft Library at U.C., Berkeley; Clapp Library, Wellesley College; Fine Arts Library at Indiana University and others.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Education: B.A., Studio Art, Art History, Latin Language and Literature, University of MA; M.F.A. Book Arts/Printmaking, University of the Arts, Philadelphia, PA.</p>','Sarah Smith has been teaching letterpress printing, bookbinding, and printmaking for ten years at Montserrat College of Art, is a founding member of Imposition Press, and has been working for the past fifteen years as a rare book conservator at the Northeast Document Conservation Center.\r\n',''),(3,'Amelia','Kassel','President','MarketingBase','amelia@marketingbase.com','<p> Amelia Kassel is President of MarketingBase, specializing in industry, company and competitive and market intelligence research since 1982. Amelia holds a Master\'s Degree in Library Science (1971, UCLA) and combines expertise in Internet research and fee-based databases with knowledge of business and marketing strategies.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Amelia taught at the University of California Berkeley Extension for 15 years, was a lecturer at San JosÃ© State University School of Library and Information Science (1992-1996), and now teaches distance education at San JosÃ© State University with courses in Online and Advanced Online Searching, Competitive Intelligence Research and New and Alternative Careers for Librarians and Information Professionals. As a recognized author and international speaker, she conducts seminars for associations and conferences and gives workshops on-site for companies and organizations. Her successful email-based Mentor Program is tailored for independent information professionals.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Amelia is a recipient of AIIP\'s Sue Rugge Memorial Award and the Gale Group Writing Award. She authored The Super Searchers on Wall Street and has written many articles for Searcher Magazine, and other information industry publications.</p>','Amelia Kassel is President and owner of MarketingBase, a firm specializing in industry, company, and competitive and market intelligence research since 1982. Amelia taught at the graduate level for 15 years at the University of California, Berkeley Extension, four years as adjunct faculty at San Jose State University School of Library and Information Science, and now teaches distance education for San Jose SLIS with courses in Online Searching, Advanced Online Searching, and Competitive Intelligence Research. She also conducts workshops and gives presentations for associations and teaches in other academic settings.  Amelia is author of <em>The Super Searchers on Wall Street</em>, contributes articles and columns to information industry publications, and operates a successful one-on-one email-based training program, <em>The Mentor Program</em>, for new searchers in corporations and for information professionals starting or expanding a research business.','http://www.marketingbase.com'),(48,'Bill','Hanscom','Project Conservation Technician','Weissman Preservation Center, Harvard University Libraries','billhanscom@gmail.com','<p>Bill Hanscom is an project conservation technician at the Weissman Preservation Center for Harvard University libraries, where he treats a broad range of special collections materials. He is also an adjunct instructor in Bookbinding at Montserrat College of Art. His work has been exhibited at the Herbert F. Johnson Museum of Art, Cornell University, Ithaca, NY; The Free Library of Philadelphia, Philadelphia, PA; Middleton Library Printmaking Gallery, Louisiana State University, Baton Rouge, LA; and Columbia College Center for Book and Paper Arts, Chicago, IL. His work is held in the collections of Columbia University, The Free Library of Philadelphia, and numerous private collections.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Education: MFA, Book Arts/Printmaking, The University of the Arts; BFA, Graphic Design, Montserrat College of Art.</p>','Bill Hanscom is an project conservation technician at the Weissman Preservation Center for Harvard University libraries',''),(5,'Danielle','Conklin','Independent Information Professional','','dc@dconklinconsulting.com','<p>Danielle Conklin is an experienced Information Professional and principal of D.Conklin Consulting. Her career-related interests include research, cataloging, and preservation. Danielle has worked in the field of library and museum services since 2004. She holds a masterâ€™s degree in Library & Information Science from Simmons College in Massachusetts and is a graduate of Saint Michaelâ€™s College in Vermont.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Danielle is a member of the American Library Association, the Association of Library Collections & Technical Services, and the Association of Independent Information Professionals. She has served on organizational committees and is actively involved in continuing education.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Although a native of the Northeast, she has traveled much of the United States. She currently lives and works in Pennsylvania.</p>','Danielle Conklin is an independent information professional living in Pennsylvania. She has previously served as a Cataloging Librarian at Kansas City (KS) Public Library and an Information Services Librarian at Cumberland County (NC) Public Library. Danielle is a graduate of Simmons College GSLIS.',''),(6,'Larry','Cooperman','','','lgc92@yahoo.com','<p>Larry Cooperman was most recently the library director at the Orlando, FL campus of Everglades University, a four-year college providing baccalaureate degrees in construction management, aviation management, alternative medicine, and business administration. He has been a librarian since receiving his MS from Simmons College in 2002, having previously worked as the library director at ITT Technical Institute (Jacksonville, FL) and as a media specialist at Seminole High School, Sanford, FL. He has served on the Northeast Florida Library and Information Network (NEFLIN) Continuing Education Committee from 2002 to 2004 (serving as Chair in his final year) and the Florida Library Association (FLA) Scholarship Committee from 2003 to 2006. He has presented a half-day workshop, IT Resources on the Internet for Librarians, at various locations; he also writes book reviews for School Library Journal, Reference & User Services Quarterly, and College & Research Libraries News. He is a full member of the Florida Library Association and the American Library Association.</p>\r\n','Larry Cooperman was most recently the library director at the Orlando, FL campus of Everglades University.',''),(7,'Robin','Brenner','Teen Librarian','','robin@noflyingnotights.com','<p>Robin has been hanging around libraries pretty much since birth. In school through to Bryn Mawr College, she volunteered and worked in libraries and thought, \"Hey, I can do that. I want to do that.\" She is currently working as the Teen Librarian in Brookline, MA. Her interests and vocation combine in her work with teenagers, and graphic novels have become her niche in the library world. She is the creator and editor in chief of the graphic novel review website, No Flying No Tights (www.noflyingnotights.com). She published \"Understanding Manga and Anime\", a guide to Japanese manga and anime, for Libraries Unlimited in June 2007, and nominated for an Eisner Award in 2008. She contributes reviews and features to publications including Library Journal, School Library Journal (Good Comics for Kids group blog contributor), VOYA, and Early Word. She has also been lucky enough to serve on a variety of committees for YALSA, including Popular Paperbacks for Young Adults, Great Graphic Novels for Teens, and as Chair of the Margaret A. Edwards Award Committee. She was a judge for the 2007 Will Eisner awards.</p>\r\n','Robin Brenner is a Reference/Teen Librarian, Brookline, MA; robin@noflyingnotights.com. Sarah Sogigian is a Trainer/Consultant for Youth Services, Metrowest MA and Boston Regional Library Systems.\r\n','http://www.noflyingnotights.com'),(8,'Beth','Gallaway','Library Trainer and Consultant','','informationgoddess29@gmail.com','<p>Beth Gallaway was named a Library Journal Mover & Shaker in 2006 for her work in advocating for videogames in libraries. She is an independent library trainer/consultant specializing in gaming, technology, and youth services, and is a YALSA certified Serving the Underserved (SUS) trainer. She has spoken at state and national library conferences, and has published articles in VOYA, YALS, Media Forum Online (the newsletter of the MA School Library Media Association), and YAttitudes, the newsletter of the Young Adult Library Services Association. Her book Game On! Gaming at the Library is available from Neal Schuman.</p>\r\n<p>A former young adult librarian, Beth is one of only seven YALSA Serving the Underserved Trainers in New England. She graduated from Simmons with a Master\'s degree in Library and Information Science in 1998. Beth is currently serving as the Assistant Director at the Haverhill (MA) Public Library.</p>','Library Journal Mover & Shaker Beth Gallaway is an independent library consultant specializing in gaming, technology, and youth services. She is currently serving as the Assistant Director at the Haverhill (MA) Public Library. ','http://informationgoddess.info'),(25,'Nicole','Hennig','Header of the User Experience Group','MIT Libraries','nic@hennigweb.com','<p>Nicole Hennig is the  Head of the User Experience Group for the <a href=\"http://libraries.mit.edu/\">MIT Libraries</a>. Her field of expertise is usable web design and usability testing, and she has spoken on this topic at conferences such as National Online and Internet Librarian. In 2001 she won the <a href=\"http://www.hennigweb.com/misc/award.html#2001\">Infinite Mile Award for Innovation and Creativity</a> given by her peers in the MIT Libraries and in 2006 she won the <a href=\"http://www.hennigweb.com/misc/award.html\">MIT Excellence Award for Innovation Solutions</a>. Before coming to MIT in January of 1999, she was the Systems Librarian for Bose Corporation in Framingham, MA, where she designed and managed the home page for the corporate Intranet. She has worked in academic, corporate, and non-profit libraries for over 15 years and was formerly a classical musician, playing pipe organ and harpsichord in the Boston area.</p>','Nicole Hennig is the Head of the User Experience Group for the MIT Libraries','http://www.hennigweb.com'),(9,'Heather','Hedden','Senior Analyst','Project Performance Corporation','heather@hedden.net','<p>Heather Hedden is a taxonomy consultant with consulting firm <a href=\"http://www.ppc.com\">Project Performance Corporation</a> and is author of <a href=\"http://www.hedden-information.com/accidental-taxonomist.htm\"><em>The Accidental Taxonomist</em></a> (Information Today, 2010). She has over 15 years of experience in the field of taxonomies. Heather worked previously as a controlled vocabulary editor at the periodical index and reference database publisher Gale (formerly Information Access Company, now Cengage Learning), as the taxonomist at with the enterprise search software vendor Viziant Corporation, as a taxonomy consultant for consultancy Earley & Associates, and as the taxonomy manager at the wind energy company First Wind. Heather has also provided taxonomy development, indexing, and training services through her own business, Hedden Information Management.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Heather is chair of the mentoring committee of the Taxonomy Division of SLA and manager of the Taxonomies and Controlled Vocabularies special interest group of the American Society for Indexing (ASI). She is also a past president of the New England Chapter of ASI. Heather has published numerous articles and given many conference presentations and workshops on taxonomy and indexing topics.</p>','Heather Hedden is a taxonomy consultant with Project Performance Corporation and author of the book \"The Accidental Taxonomist\" (2010). She is manager of the Taxonomies & Controlled Vocabularies special interest group of the American Society for Indexing and is chair of the Mentoring Committee of the Taxonomy Division of SLA.','http://www.hedden-information.com'),(46,'Kathryn Hammond','Baker','Deputy Director','Center for the History of Medicine, Countway Library of Medicine, Harvard University','kbaker@hms.harvard.edu','<p>Kathryn had her first archival experience as a 16 year old researcher in the correspondence of First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt at the Roosevelt Presidential Library in Hyde Park, New York â€” after that, there was no turning back. She spent considerable time in museums, historical societies, and archives, for fun and profit, eventually earning a Masters in history and discovering records management. During her tenure at the Massachusetts Archives, Kathryn combined records management and appraisal and was initiated into the joys of MARC by Simmons alum Nancy Richard. Kathryn had the good fortune to attend Simmons GSLIS and take reference with Allen Smith and Systems Analysis with Robin Peek. She continues to believe that convergence is not just for technology and that information science, library science, archives, and records management must and should increasingly converge. She is currently overseeing a CLIR \"Hidden Collections\" manuscripts processing grant in the history of public health policy and is Principal Investigator for the Center for the History of Medicine\'s participation in a Sloan-funded project to digitize rare medical texts to create a freely-available online \"Medical Heritage Library.\"</p>','Kathryn Hammond Baker is the Deputy Director for the Center for the History of Medicine, Countway Library, Harvard Medical School.',''),(10,'Marta','Deyrup','Professor and Librarian I','Seton Hall University Libraries','curtdeyrup@aol.com','<p>Marta Deyrup is Professor/Librarian I at Seton Hall University Libraries. She is the author/editor of three books and has written scholarly articles, news pieces, interviews, and book reviews for publications that include Library Administration & Management, College & Research Libraries,Technical Services Quarterly, Cataloging & Classification Quarterly, the New York Times, Publishers Weekly, Slavic and East European Journal, and Slavic and Eastern European Information Resources. She is on the editorial board of Technical Services Quarterly, is the acquisitions editor for LITA publications, and is the former editor of Library Administration & Management. Marta received her Ph.D. from Columbia University and her M.L.S. from Rutgers SCILS.</p>','Marta Deyrup  is Professor/Librarian I at Seton Hall University Libraries.',''),(45,'Kimberly','Mitchell','Reference & Education Librarian','Albany College of Pharmacy and Health Sciences','kimberly.mitchell@acphs.edu','<p>Kim Mitchell, Reference & Education Librarian, Albany College of Pharmacy and Health Sciences, obtained her MLS from Simmons College. She has been a speaker at regional and national library conferences. She is the eBookshelf column editor for the \"Journal of Electronic Resources in Medical Libraries\" and a contributor to the forthcoming edition of \"The Medical Library\r\nAssociation Encyclopedic Guide to Searching and Finding Health Information on the Web\". She teaches drug information workshops for public librarians and is an expert searcher for the National Library of Medicine\'s Healthy People 2020 Information Access Project. In her spare time Kim writes fiction and is currently seeking\r\nrepresentation for her literary mystery, <em>The Red Priests</em>.</p>','Kim Mitchell is the Reference & Education Librarian at Albany College of Pharmacy and Health Sciences.','http://kimberlymitchell.info'),(11,'James','DaMico','Graphics Project Archivist','Rhode Island Historical Society Library','james.damico@gmail.com','<p>James DaMico holds a Master\'s of Library and Information Sciences (MLIS) from the University of Pittsburgh and a Bachelor of Arts in Film and Video Production from the Rochester Institute of Technology.  James is the Graphics Project Archivist at the Rhode Island Historical Society Library (RIHS) where he is surveying and creating core catalog records of the entire Graphics Collection.  James is responsible for compiling accurate data on the scope of the collection, setting preservation and disaster recovery priorities, appraising items to ensure they fit the collection policy of the Society and assessing the preservation and conservation needs of the collection as well as re-housing items.  In addition, James is cataloging the 16mm newsreel footage of former Providence Mayor Vincent A. Cianci.  James is interested in the preservation and making accessible photographic and moving image material to the public.  James also teaches workshops and lectures on the history of photographic technology and the care and identification of audio-visual and photographic material.  Prior to becoming an Archivist, James worked as an Audio-Visual Technician for Microsoft and professionally in the film and video field as a cameraman, editor, soundperson, and lighting technician.</p>\r\n','James DaMico  is the Graphics Project Archivist at the Rhode Island Historical Society Library (RIHS) where he is surveying and creating core catalog records of the entire Graphics Collection.\r\n','http://jdamico68.wordpress.com/'),(12,'Betsy','Diamant-Cohen','Director','Mother Goose on the Loose &reg;','betsydc@mgol.org','<p>Dr. Betsy Diamant-Cohen, creator of Mother Goose on the LooseÂ®, was named a Mover and Shaker by Library Journal in 2004.  Author of four books for children\'s librarians, she has had experience working in libraries in the US and abroad for more than 25 years . She travels around the country presenting training workshops for librarians, offers a telephone courses for the Ontario Library Association and has spoken at numerous conferences.</p>\r\n','Dr. Betsy Diamant-Cohen, creator of Mother Goose on the Loose &reg;, was named a Mover and Shaker by Library Journal in 2004. Author of four books for children\'s librarians, she has had experience working in libraries in the US and abroad for more than 25 years . She travels around the country presenting training workshops for librarians, offers a telephone courses for the Ontario Library Association, and has spoken at numerous conferences.',''),(13,'Seth','Maislin','','','seth.maislin@potomacindexing.com','<p>Seth is a taxonomy and indexing consultant, specializing in the construction of navigable information hierarchies, knowledge classifications, retrieval systems, and indexes. He is an industry leader in editorial tagging, taxonomy, and search and database keywording. He teaches a comprehensive remote-learning class on indexing through Middlesex Community College and speaks at numerous conferences and companies. He is past-president of the American Society for Indexing (ASI) and continues to be involved in professional development and indexer advocacy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Seth is a managing partner of <a href=\"http://www.potomacindexing.com/\">Potomac Indexing</a>, an indexing firm with over 100 clients and dozens of professional indexers. He is a senior taxonomy consultant with <a href=\"http://www.earley.com/\">Earley & Associates</a>, an information management company with a specialty in taxonomy, and has presented on or moderated numerous Taxonomy Community of Practice (TaxoCoP) calls. Past positions have include Integration Manager at <a href=\"http://www.lycos.com/\">Terra Lycos</a> and Senior Indexer at <a href=\"http://www.oreilly.com/\">Oâ€™Reilly & Associates</a>, and he has consulted with the likes of the United Nations Library, Massachusetts Institute of Technology, and numerous corporations like Mercedes-Benz, PeopleSoft, Caterpillar, Mattel, Comverse (Israel), and Motorola.</p>\r\n','Seth Maislin is a leader in the indexing industry. He is a managing partner of indexing firm Potomac Indexing, past-president of the American Society for Indexing, and founder of the techindexing community. He teaches a comprehensive remote-learning class on indexing and has spoken at numerous conferences and companies. Also, his indexing expertise extends into consulting and training work in information architecture and taxonomy.','www.potomacindexing.com'),(14,'Mary','Minow','Library Law Consultant','','simmons@librarylaw.com','<p>Mary Minow is a library law consultant, specializing in copyright, privacy and free speech. She has consulted for the Library of Congress, the California State Library and numerous other library organizations across the country. She manages the <a href=\"http://fairuse.stanford.edu/\">Stanford Copyright & Fair Use</a>, which recently started the FairlyUsed twitter feed.</p>\r\n','Mary Minow, J.D., A.M.L.S. is a Library Law consultant at librarylaw.com.',''),(15,'Bonnie','Peirce','Head of Children\'s Services','Dover Town Library','wizardhere@gmail.com','<p>Bonnie Peirce is Head of Children\'s Services at the Dover Town Library and was recently profiled in Library Journal\'s Movers and Shakers as a \'Web 2.0 guru\'.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Bonnie is the founder of <a href=\"http://www.b3ok.org\">B3OK</a>, an open global mobile knowledge network connecting the physical and digital worlds.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>She is also co-founder and CTO of <a href=\"http://thebestkidsbooksite.com/\">thebestkidsbooksite.com</a>, a growing and unique knowledge brokering service serving child-focused professionals and families around the world, and founder of the Library Goddesses Blog Network, a collaborative blog network with companion wikis to enable librarians across the United States and Canada to share their knowledge of books and their professional experience with many different aspects of librarianship. Bonnie is a graduate of GSLIS, received her business degree from Thunderbird and did her undergraduate work at Dartmouth College.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Bonnie has traveled extensively, is an avid podcaster, blogger, and advocate for incorporating new media tools and practices into public library services, and has an abiding interest in global literacy.</p>','Bonnie Peirce is Head of Children\'s Services at the Dover Town Library and was recently profiled in Library Journal\'s Movers and Shakers as a \'Web 2.0 guru\'. Bonnie is the founder of B3OK, an open global mobile knowledge network connecting the physical and digital worlds. She is an avid advocate for incorporating new media tools and mobile devices into public library services.','http://www.thebestkidsbooksite.com'),(16,'Rebekah','Kilzer','Emerging Technologies Librarian','Drexel University Libraries','rebekah@drexel.edu','<p>Rebekah Kilzer is the Emerging Technologies Librarian at Drexel University Libraries where she works with library staff to discover, research and implement methods for fruitful and effective interactions with students and faculty. Her background in Systems and Technical Services provides a well-rounded perspective on library work. In addition to managing many library projects, she\'s created successful plans for sharing technological information for librarians and library staff with varying levels of experience. She is also an adjunct instructor at Drexel University\'s iSchool, with experience teaching Cataloging and Metadata courses in the MS/LIS program.</p>\r\n','Rebekah Kilzer is currently the Emerging Technologies Librarian at Drexel University Libraries where she works with library staff to discover, research and implement methods for fruitful and effective interactions with students and faculty. Her background in Systems and Technical Services provides a well-rounded perspective on library work. She is also an adjunct instructor at Drexel University\'s iSchool, teaching in the MS/LIS program.',''),(17,'Katherine','Bertolucci','Information Management Consultant','Isis Information Services','katherine@isisinform.com','<p>Katherine Bertolucci is an information management consultant and owner of Isis Information Services in Phoenix, AZ. She specializes in persuasive information strategies for subject-based classifications, hierarchical taxonomies, and other information structures.  Known for her work with Snoopy, Katherine\'s programs are entertaining and informative. A pioneer in non-traditional classification, Katherine built her first taxonomy in 1978. Clients include poets and transnational corporations such as Procter & Gamble and Thomson Financial. She is a former Chair of SLAâ€™s Leadership & Management Division. Print publications include \"The Future Still Awaits Us: Ray Kurzweil\'s Singularity on Wall Street\" (Searcher, 07-08/09), â€œBeyond Findability: Organizing Information in the Age of the Miscellaneousâ€ (Searcher, 02/09), and â€œHappiness Is Taxonomy: Four Structures for Snoopyâ€ (Information Outlook, 03/03).</p>','Katherine Bertolucci is an information management consultant and owner of Isis Information Services in Phoenix, AZ.','http://www.isisinform.com'),(18,'Jason','Puckett','Librarian for Communication and Educational Technologies','Georgia State University','jason@librarianx.net','<p>Jason Puckett is Librarian for Communication and Educational Technologies at Georgia State University in Atlanta. He\'s the liaison for the Communication Department and works with instructional technologies, online teaching methods, and face-to-face classes. He received his MLIS from The Florida State University School of Library & Information Studies in 2008 and has worked in libraries since 1993. Jason was named a <em>Library Journal</em> Mover & Shaker in 2010.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Jason is the author of the forthcoming book <em>Zotero: A Guide for Librarians, Researchers and Educators</em> (ACRL Publications, spring 2011). He speaks and writes about library technology topics including podcasting, digital rights management, and open-source research tools. He\'s co-host and co-producer of the monthly <a href=\"http://adlibinstruction.blogspot.com/\">Adventures in Library Instruction</a> podcast, and he blogs at <a href=\"http://jasonpuckett.net/\">Librarian X</a>. He has lived in Thailand and in his spare time is a video gamer and fan of science fiction, comics and B-movies.</p>\r\n','Jason Puckett  is Librarian for Communication and Educational Technologies at GSU in Atlanta and a 2010 Library Journal Mover & Shaker. He writes and speaks about open-source software in libraries (pro), digital rights management (anti), and teaching information literacy (pro). He podcasts at <a href=\"http://adlibinstruction.blogspot.com/\">Adventures in Library Instruction</a> and blogs at <a href=\"http://jasonpuckett.net/\">Librarian X</a>. He\'s the author of a forthcoming book about using and teaching Zotero (ACRL Publications, spring 2011).','http://jasonpuckett.net'),(19,'Pamela','MacKellar','Library Consultant, Author','','pmackellar182@gmail.com','<p>Pamela MacKellar is an author and library consultant who has been a librarian for over 25 years. She has held positions as a newspaper librarian, library director, assistant librarian, health sciences librarian, cataloger, technology consultant, and independent consultant in libraries of all kinds including special, school, public, post-secondary, tribal, prison, and state library agency. Pam holds an MLS from the State University of New York at Albany.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Author of <em>The Accidental Librarian</em> (Information Today Inc., 2008), Pam has also co-written <em>Winning Grants: A Multimedia How-To-Do-It Manual for Librarians with Multimedia Tutorials and Grant Development Tools</em> (Neal-Schuman, 2010) and <em>Grants for Libraries: a How-To-Do-It Manual</em> (Neal-Schuman, 2006). She wrote â€œSix Preparedness Strategies for Librarians in Tough Economic Timesâ€ in <em>Computers in Libraries</em> (April, 2010) and co-wrote the feature article in <em>Computers in Libraries</em> (July-August, 2006) â€œWishing Wonâ€™t Work: 10 Things You Need to Know and Do When Applying for Technology Grants.â€ Pam co-developed â€œGrant Writing Basicsâ€, a web tutorial for the University of North Texas School of Library and Information Sciences and she co-hosts the <a href=\"http://www.librarygrants.blogspot.com\">Library Grants blog</a>. She has presented at the Computers in Libraries Conference, Internet Librarian Conference, the Quebec Library Association Annual Conference and the New Mexico Library Association Annual Conference. Pam has taught classes and workshops on grants for libraries and non-profits, written successful proposals for government and foundation grants, administered grant projects and reviewed grant proposals for federal and state agencies. She is the recipient of the 2010 Loleta D. Fyan Award from the American Library Association for â€œOnline Management Course for New Library Directors in New Mexico.â€ Currently Pam is writing her newest book, <em>Writing Technology Grants</em>, to be published by Neal-Schuman Publishers as part of the LITA Guides series.</p>','Pamela MacKellar is an author and library consultant who has been a librarian for over 25 years.','http://www.pamelamackellar.com'),(44,'Vivienne','Piroli','Health Sciences Librarian','Simmons College','vivienne.piroli@simmons.edu','<p>Vivienne Piroli is the School of Health Sciences Librarian at Simmons College. She is also an adjunct faculty member at the Graduate School of Library and Information Science at Simmons.  In her role as SHS Librarian she is responsible for providing student and faculty support for programs in Healthcare Administration, Nursing, Nutrition and Physical Therapy. Vivienne places particular emphasis on Information Literacy instruction for these groups and finds it is symbiotic with curricula based in Evidence Based Medicine. As an adjunct Vivienne teaches a course on User Instruction which is designed to teach budding librarians how to design Information Literacy instruction according to professional standards and pedagogically sound practices. She has authored several articles and book chapters on a range of information literacy topics. She was nominated for the 2009 Association of Library and Information Science Educators\' Excellence in Teaching, award. She received her undergraduate education from University College Dublin, Ireland and holds a postgraduate Higher Diploma in Education from Trinity College Dublin. Vivienne has received a Master\'s degree in history from Harvard University and her Master\'s in Library and Information Science from Simmons College.</p>','Vivienne Piroli is the School of Health Sciences Librarian at Simmons College.',''),(20,'Rebecca','Metzger','Reference & Instruction Librarian','','metzgerr@lafayette.edu','<p>Before becoming a librarian, Rebecca Metzger was a marketing and public relations specialist for art museums, arts organizations, and individual artists. During this time, she placed articles in the New York Times, Wall Street Journal, Vogue, Village Voice and on NPR and NY1 television, among other major news outlets. She also secured commissions and raised funds for artist projects. As a Reference and Instruction Librarian at Lafayette College, she has founded a student advisory committee, initiated programs geared to first year students and parents, created a Facebook page and built an online fan base for the library, helped to increase hours and visibility of IM reference, and partnered with the Counseling Center, Writing Center, and Parents Program. She is an academic advisor, a faculty advisor to the Hillel student organization, has served as the Provost-appointed chair of the College\'s Jewish Studies Advisory Committee, and was recently elected the chair of the faculty\'s Teaching and Learning Committee. While her initial job description included only a small marketing focus - to produce a semi-annual newsletter - she has successfully adapted her prior marketing skills to her job as a librarian, thus raising the visibility of the library\'s services across campus.</p>','Rebecca Metzger  is a Reference and Instruction Librarian at Lafayette College\'s Skillman Library in Easton, PA. In addition to regular reference and instruction duties, Rebecca heads Skillman Library\'s outreach efforts. She runs a student advisory board, organizes orientations and open houses for students and parents, produces a newsletter for faculty, and promotes library services to students through online and offline communications. On campus, she is a faculty advisor to Hillel Society, an academic advisor, and the chair of the faculty\'s Teaching and Learning Committee. Off campus, she is currently the chair of ACRL\'s Instruction Section\'s Management and Leadership Committee. She has been published in Library Journal and NMRT Footnotes, was selected to participate in ACRL\'s Immersion 2008 program, and is currently serving as an ALA Emerging Leader. Rebecca graduated from Simmons GSLIS in January 2006.',''),(21,'Linda','Dunn','Sole Proprietor','Dunn Information Organization','linda47dunn@yahoo.com','<p>Linda Dunn is a freelance periodical/database indexer and sole proprietor of Dunn Information Organization.  She has been indexing periodicals for thirty years, first for print indexes and more recently for databases.  Since 2007, she has been indexing English and French journals for a European-based database.  Linda has presented several workshops on periodical indexing and creating controlled vocabularies, including an online workshop for Simmons College GSLICE in January 2011.  She has a Masters of Library Science from the University of California at Berkeley and a Masters in Film History from the University of Iowa, Iowa City, Iowa.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Linda is a member of the American Society for Indexing and has presented several workshops on periodical indexing and creating controlled vocabularies for ASI chapters.  Currently she is the Immediate Past President of the New England Chapter of the American Society for Indexing <a href=\"http://www.newenglandindexers.org\">(www.newenglandindexers.org)</a>.  She is the founder and former manager of the Periodical/Database Indexing Special Interest Group of ASI.</p>','Linda Dunn is a freelance periodical/database indexer with thirty years experience.  Since 2007, she has been indexing English and French journals for a European-based database.  She has presented several workshops on periodical indexing and creating controlled vocabularies, including an online workshop on periodical indexing for Simmons College GSLICE in January 2011.',''),(22,'Bill','Wisser','Instructional Designer in the Department of Academic Technology','Simmons College','bill.wisser@simmons.edu','<p>Bill Wisser is an Instructional Designer in the Department of Academic Technology at Simmons College. He helps faculty re-conceptualize their traditional classes for online or blended delivery. He holds a Ph.D. in history from the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill and brings over seven years of classroom experience in both small and large universities to the position. Recently, he served as coordinator for an initiative to develop and disseminate an academic writing support tool to all North Carolina system schools. He is interested in efforts to support students in the learning process and ensuring that effective teaching practices are maintained in the online environment.</p>\r\n','Bill Wisser is an Instructional Designer in the Department of Academic Technology at Simmons College. He helps faculty re-conceptualize their traditional classes for online or blended delivery. He holds a Ph.D. in history from the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill and brings over seven years of classroom experience in both small and large universities to the position.',''),(23,'Cheryl','Kohen','Emerging Technologies Librarian','Daytona State College','cheryl.kohen@gmail.com','<p>Cheryl is currently the Emerging Technologies Librarian at Daytona State College and was the Career Resource Librarian at Simmons College for three years. She graduated from both the Simmons College undergraduate program as a double major in English and Philosophy, as well as receiving her master\'s degree from the Simmons College Graduate School of Library and Information Science. Cheryl also reviews career resources for the publication \"Choice Review,\" a premier source for reviews of academic books, electronic media, and Internet resources of interest to those in higher education. Additionally, Cheryl ran a Career Center at the Massachusetts Library Association Annual Conference in May 2008 and 2009 where she helped current librarians search for job opportunities and professional development.</p>','Emerging Technologies Librarian, Daytona State College',''),(24,'Michael','LaMagna','Coordinator of Electronic Resources','Cabrini College Holy Spirit Library','mlamagna@dccc.edu','<p>Michael LaMagna is an Assistant Professor/Reference Librarian, Liaison for Information Literacy and Distance Learning at Delaware County Community College.  Most recently Michael served as the Coordinator of Electronic Resources at Cabrini College.  He looks for ways to use technology to reach students, faculty, and staff and has been involved with using Google applications to expand and develop services at his library. He also serves as an adjunct assistant professor at the University of Maryland University College. He holds an undergraduate and a graduate degree in history and a graduate degree in library and information science.</p>\r\n','Michael LaMagna is an Assistant Professor/Reference Librarian, Liaison for Information Literacy and Distance Learning at Delaware County Community College.',''),(27,'Chris','Castaldi','Game Instructor','','chris.castaldi@gmail.com','<p>Chris Castaldi is a master\'s degree candidate in game development at the University of Advancing Technology in Phoenix, AZ. He facilitated 3 week-long game design camps in Glendale (AZ) Public Library in summer 2008, presented on Gaming at the Arizona State Library Teen Summit, and will be working on a game design unit for a Phoenix Public Library grant in 2009.</p>\r\n','','http://discoveringgame.com/'),(28,'Kelly','Czarnecki','Technology Education Librarian','','kczarnecki@plcmc.org','<p>Kelly Czarnecki, Technology Education Librarian, ImaginOn, Public Library of Charlotte and Mecklenburg County, Library Journal Mover and Shaker (2007), and Writer for SLJ column, \"The Gaming Life.\"</p>\r\n','',''),(29,'Patricia','Deyton','Director, Center for Gender in Organizations and Senior Lecturer','Simmons School of Management','patricia.deyton@simmons.edu','<p>Patricia H. Deyton is the Faculty Director of the Center for Gender in Organizations (CGO), the internationally recognized research arm of the Simmons School of Management in Boston. At Simmons, Ms. Deyton is also a Senior Lecturer in both the MBA and Undergraduate Programs, teaching courses in Gender and Leadership, Managing Diversity, Organizational Change, Nonprofit Management and Introduction to Management.  In addition she teaches at Gender, Leadership and Management, and Nonprofit Management at the Harvard University Extension School and Principles of Management at the Graduate School of Library and Information Science (GSLIS) at Simmons and the capstone course on Leadership in the Ph.D. program at GSLIS.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Prior to joining Simmons in the summer of 2004, Ms. Deyton was the Executive Director of the Council of Women World Leaders based at the John F. Kennedy School of Government at Harvard University, where she had responsibility for the oversight of the strategy, program development and implementation, operations and funding of the Council.  The Council is comprised of current and former heads of state and government and works to mobilize the experience, network, knowledge and global visibility of the women who hold or have held the highest offices in their own country.  The Council moved to Washington, D.C. in 2004 and Ms. Deyton continues her role with the Council as the Senior Advisor.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>From 1989 to 2001, Ms. Deyton was Chief Executive Officer of the American Red Cross of Massachusetts Bay.  During her tenure the organization doubled in size of programs and budget.  She was active in many national and international programs, leading delegations to Cambodia and Macedonia.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ms. Deyton has served on numerous boards of directors and public commissions and currently serves as a trustee of the Longy School of Music and the United Methodist Foundation of New England.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>She actively trains and speaks on issues relating to gender, negotiations, womenâ€™s leadership, and principled leadership.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ms. Deyton holds a Masters of Social Work from Columbia University, a Masters of Divinity from Yale University, certificates in management from the Kellogg School at Northwestern University and the Harvard Kennedy School and a certificate in Ethics from the Darden School at the University of Virginia.</p>','',''),(30,'Eleta','Exline','Digital Collections Librarian','University of New Hampshire','eleta.exline@unh.edu','<p>Eleta Exline graduated from Syracuse University with a MSLIS and a Certificate of Advanced Studies in Digital Libraries. She has been the University of New Hampshire Library\'s Digital Collections Librarian since October 2005; her current task at UNH is to develop policies and procedures for the digital initiative and to implement a digital asset management system. Previously, Eleta was the archivist for a contemporary sculpture studio in Rochester, New York and worked on brittle books scanning and microfilming projects at Mann Library, Cornell University.</p>\r\n','Eleta Exline has been the University of New Hampshire Library\'s Digital Collections Librarian since October 2005. Her current task at UNH is to develop policies and procedures for the digital initiative and to implement a digital asset management system.',''),(31,'Irene','Hansen','Reference Librarian','Wisconsin Historical Society','ihansen@wisc.edu','<p>Irene Hansen is an Associate Lecturer in Library and Information Studies at the University of Wisconsin-Madison, with a background in genealogy.  She also is a reference librarian at the Wisconsin Historical Society.  Irene has worked at the Local & Family History Section of The Newberry Library, the Special Collections Dept. of the University of Illinois at Chicago, the Illinois Historical Survey in Urbana-Champaign, and the Genealogy Dept. of the Allen County Public Library, Fort Wayne, Indiana.</p>','Irene Hansen is an Associate Lecturer in Library and Information Studies at the University of Wisconsin-Madison, with a background in genealogy.  She also is a reference librarian at the Wisconsin Historical Society.',''),(32,'Rex','Krajewski','Reference Librarian','Simmons College Library','rex.krajewski@simmons.edu','<p>Rex Krajewski is a Reference Librarian at the Simmons College Library. For more information, please see <a href=\"http://web.simmons.edu/~krajewsk/index.html\">http://web.simmons.edu/~krajewsk/index.html</a>.</p>\r\n','Rex Krajewski is a Reference Librarian at the Simmons College Library.','http://web.simmons.edu/~krajewsk/index.html'),(33,'Martha','Mahard','Adjunct Faculty','Simmons Graduate School of Library and Information Science','martha.mahard@simmons.edu','<p>Martha Mahard has more than three decades of professional experience with the Harvard College Library System, including work in photography and visual collections at the Fine Arts Library, visual resources at the Harvard Graduate School of Design, and the Harvard Theatre Collection of The Houghton Library. She has written numerous publications and presentations in the field of photographic archives and visual information. Mahard received her D.A. and M.S. from the Simmons Graduate School of Library and Information Science.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lecturer in <em>LIS 424 - Moving Image Collections in Libraries and Archives,  LIS 444 - Archiving and Preserving Digital Media, LIS 446 - Art Documentation, LIS 470 - Visual Communication, LIS 471 - Photographic Archives and Visual Information</em>. Martha Mahard also teaches workshops for GSLIS Continuing Education.</p>','',''),(34,'Theresa','Maturevich','Head of Reference','Bedford Free Public Library','maturevich@gmail.com','<p>Theresa Maturevich is a Simmons GSLIS alum and Head of Reference at the Bedford Free Public Library in Bedford, MA.</p>','Theresa Maturevich is a Simmons GSLIS alum and Head of Reference at the Bedford Free Public Library in Bedford, MA.',''),(35,'Stacy','Schwartz','Research & Instruction Librarian','Worcester Polytechnic Institute','sschwartz@wpi.edu','<p>Stacy Schwartz is the Research & Instruction Librarian at Worcester Polytechnic Institute. She was most recently the Library Assistant for Reference and Information Literacy at the Simmons College Library. She participates in planning and coordinating reference services and library instruction. Stacy has created a variety of tutorials using Captivate for the Beatley Library.   She has spoken at state conferences, ran the \"Technology Corner\" of the Teaching and Learning Center at MLA and currently serves as Secretary for the New England Library Instruction Group (NELIG).  Stacy will have her Masters Degree in Library and Information Science this December and holds a B.S. from Cornell University.</p>','Stacy Schwartz is the Research & Instruction Librarian at Worcester Polytechnic Institute.',''),(36,'Evan','Simpson','Head of Reference and Instruction','Tisch Library, Tufts University','evandsimpson@gmail.com','<p>Evan Simpson is the Head of Reference and Instruction for the Tisch Library at Tufts University, where he leads the development of research assistance services and instruction programs for a broad range of research communities in the School of Arts, Sciences, and Engineering. Evan is responsible for identifying and promoting emerging research and instruction technologies and for cultivating collaborative initiatives between reference and other library and non-library departments and programs throughout the University. Evan has long been involved in resource sharing services where he has direct experience managing interlibrary loan and document delivery units, developing new resource sharing services, and building partnerships with libraries and consortia. Evan is interested in the affect of digitization on research, instruction, and resource sharing; trends in scholarly communication; marketing and outreach for libraries; emerging technologies and their integration in instruction programs as well as discovery and delivery systems; and in Resource Sharing as a developing strategy for academic and public libraries.</p>\r\n','',''),(37,'Sarah','Sogigian','Advisor, Youth Services','Massachusetts Library System','sarah@masslibsystem.org','<p>Sarah Sogigian is an Advisor for Youth Services at the Massachusetts Library System. She previously worked as the Young Adult Librarian and in other positions at the Shrewsbury Public Library in Shrewsbury, MA where she started working as a teenager. Her favorite teen author is Anthony Horowitz, and her favorite video game is The Legend of Zelda, which is loaded onto her cell phone for emergency game playing.</p>\r\n','',''),(38,'Jean','Wilkins','Consultant','','jswilkins42@gmail.com','<p>Jean is a library consultant. Her areas of interest are leadership and change management. She is a former director of the Illinois State Library.  She is on the board of The Hope Institute for Children And Families in Springfield, Illinois. She lives in Springfield, Illinois and Tucson, Arizona.</p>\r\n','',''),(41,'James','Gehrt','Digitization Center Coordinator','Mount Holyoke College','jgehrt@mtholyoke.edu','<p>James Gehrt is the Digitization Center Coordinator at Mt. Holyoke College. James has been a fine art and professional photographer for 18 years, and a lab manager at a photographic conservation and digitization lab for 7 years (The Chicago Albumen Works).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Working as the Digitization Center Coordinator at Mt. Holyoke College for the past 5 years, James has established the Digitization Center as a service point for the community and has implemented digitizing standards and workflow in addition to managing a staff of student workers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In 2008 and 2009, James was selected as a NITLE Technology Fellow in the  area of digitization technologies</p>','James Gehrt is the Digitization Center Coordinator at Mt. Holyoke College.','http://frontporcheditions.com/'),(47,'Emily R. Novak','Gustainis','Collections Services Archivist','Center for the History of Medicine, Countway Library of Medicine, Harvard Medical School','ern6@hms.harvard.edu','<p>Emily R. Novak Gustainis (M.L.S.) is the Collections Services Archivist for the Center for the History of Medicine, Countway Library, Harvard Medical School. She collaboratively leads the Centerâ€™s descriptive program and processing metrics initiative with the objective of establishing, modifying, and enhancing descriptive practices at the Center and improving access to collections. Prior to her appointment at the Center, Gustainis served as librarian/archivist for Historic New England, working on a wide variety of descriptive, reference, research, and public access projects. Additional professional experiences include working as a photograph cataloger at the Schlesinger Library, Radcliffe Institute, for a digital access project funded by the Andrew W. Mellon Foundation and as an archivist for the Information and Archival Services Division of the Winthrop Group, Inc., where she arranged and described collections for a wide variety of corporate and nonprofit clients, including the Architectural Research Institute (Beverly Willis Papers Project), the United Nations, and WGBH. She holds both an M.L.S. and a B.A. in English Literature and Teacher Education from the State University of New York at Albany.</p>\r\n','Emily R. Novak Gustainis (MLS) has been the Collections Services Archivist for the Center for the History of Medicine, Countway Library, Harvard Medical School, for the past two years, collaboratively leading the Centerâ€™s descriptive program and processing metrics initiative.',''),(51,'Megan','Frazer Blakemore','','','megan@meganfrazer.com','<p>Librarian by day, writer by night!</p>\r\n			\r\n<p>Megan Frazer is an author for young adults. Her first novel, <em>Secrets of Truth & Beauty</em>, was published by Disney-Hyperion in July of 2009. She graduated from Columbia with a degree in English and was in the first class to complete the Undergraduate Creative Writing Certificate Program. She earned her Masterâ€™s in Library Science from Simmons GSLIS. Currently, she is enrolled in the University of Maineâ€™s Master of Education in Literacy with a Concentration in Writing and the Teaching of Writing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Working under her married name, Megan Blakemore is a high school librarian in Maine. In addition to information literacy, she focuses on raising reading achievement and giving voice to students through such programming as Coffee Houses, a Film Festival, and various reading incentives.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>She has written for <a href=\"http://www.ala.org/ala/mgrps/divs/aasl/aaslpubsandjournals/knowledgequest/kqweb.cfm\">Knowledge Quest</a> and reviewed for <a href=\"http://www.linworth.com/lmc/\">Library Media Connection</a>. You can find her occasionally opining about or reporting on issues of interest to librarians serving teens at the <a href=\"http://yalsa.ala.org/blog/\">YALSA blog</a>.</p>','Megan Frazer is an author for young adults and a high school librarian in Maine.','http://www.meganfrazer.com'),(52,'James','Erbe','','','jlerbe@gmail.com','<p>James L. Erbe (Jim) is a veteran of forty-one years in education, having taught junior high and high school English and speech, served as drama technical director at three schools, and the coordinator of fine and performing arts for the Cedar Rapids, Iowa, Community School District.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He began his online teaching career in 1998 with the University of Northern Iowa where he taught Web Page Design for Educators and Web Page Design for Media Specialists. He currently teaches Web Page Design for Educators and Assessment in E-Learning for the University of Wisconsin - Stout. He also edits online courses for the Colorado State University - Global Campus.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Jim and his wife live in suburban Orlando, FL, just a few miles from Walt Disney World.</p>','James L. Erbe (Jim) is a veteran of forty-one years in education, having taught junior high and high school English and speech, served as drama technical director at three schools, and the coordinator of fine and performing arts for the Cedar Rapids, Iowa, Community School District',''),(53,'Sarah','Ludwig','Academic Technology Coordinator','Hamden Hall Country Day School','sarah.ludwig@gmail.com','<p>Sarah Ludwig is the Academic Technology Coordinator at Hamden Hall Country Day School, an independent preschool through grade 12 school in Hamden, CT. Previously, she worked as the head of the teen department in a public library and the director of a boarding school library. Sarah\'s book, Starting from Scratch: Building a Teen Library Program from the Ground Up, will be published in June 2011 by Libraries Unlimited. In 2010, she was selected as an ALA Emerging Leader.</p>\r\n','Sarah Ludwig is the Academic Technology Coordinator at Hamden Hall Country Day School. In 2010 she was selected as an ALA Emerging Leader.','http://sarahludwig.wordpress.com/'),(54,'Shaoping','Moss','Information Technology Consultant','Mount Holyoke College','smoss@mtholyoke.edu','<p>Shaoping Moss is the Information Technology Consultant at Mount Holyoke College (MHC), MA. She was one of the recipients of the IMLS funded National Leadership grant â€œPublishing TEI Documents for Small Liberal Arts Colleges: Planning a Service, Building a Communityâ€ in 2009.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The services she provided at MHC include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Technology workshops including creating digital story telling, basic video editing, image editing, wikis, presentations, using ella tools</li>\r\n<li>Technology projects using database, XML/TEI text encoding and multimedia tools</li>\r\n<li>Custom instruction classes in library research including introduction to library research at Mt. Holyoke, locating scholarly materials, evaluating sources, using discipline specific databases, effective web tools for research</li>\r\n<li>One on one consultations to develop and support the use of technology tools and/or research projects in courses</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Besides supporting XML/TEI projects at MHC she has taught Intro to XML and XSL, and Intro to TEI and XSLT workshops at Simmons Graduate School of Library and Information Science Institutes for Continuing Education.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>She earned a materâ€™s degree in Library and Information Science from Simmons College, and a masterâ€™s degree in English Literature from Teacherâ€™s University in Hunan, China.</p>','Shaoping Moss is the Information Technology Consultant at Mount Holyoke College (MHC), MA. She was one of the recipients of the IMLS funded National Leadership grant â€œPublishing TEI Documents for Small Liberal Arts Colleges: Planning a Service, Building a Communityâ€ in 2009.',''),(55,'Amy','Deschenes','Library Technology Specialist','Simmons College Library','amy.deschenes@simmons.edu','Amy Deschenes is the Library Technology Specialist at the Simmons College Library.  She has been involved with library technology projects including website redesign, mobile web and app development, and virtual reference.  She has taught workshops at the GSLIS Technology Lab on virtual reference solutions and mobile website development.  Amy assisted facilitating the MLA Annual Conference\'s Career Center in 2010 and helped run the Technology Uncommons at ALA Midwinter 2009.  Recently, she presented at NERCOMP 2011 on Successful Strategies for Mobile Web and App Development.  Amy will have her Masters Degree in Library and Information Science in August of 2011 and holds a B.A. from Sacred Heart University.','Amy Deschenes is the Library Technology Specialist at the Simmons College Library.  She has been involved with library technology projects including website redesign, mobile web and app development, and virtual reference.','');
