INSERT INTO `workshop` VALUES (1,'Fantastic Non-Fiction for Teens','<p>Not your typical Non-Fiction, the titles and subgenres covered in this online course will give participants the opportunity to discover multiple formats and styles guaranteed to spice up collections, reader\'s advisory, and literature-based programs for teens. Non-Fiction for reluctant and avid tween and teen readers (as well as crossover appeal for adults) will ensure that your Dewey sections will circulate and become a new hot spot for patrons and students alike.</p>','online','2010-10-01','2010-10-31','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',1,0,0,0,0,'Children\'s/YA/School Librarianship',NULL),(2,'Taxonomies and Controlled Vocabularies','<p><a href=\"http://www.hedden-information.com/GSLIS-taxonomies.htm\">Preview this workshop.</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Taxonomies are becoming popular for organizing information in business knowledge management, enterprise content management systems, and intranets. Are these taxonomies different from literature retrieval thesauri? How does one go about creating a taxonomy? This online workshop will provide recommended best practices for how to create terms, relationships, and variants for different kinds of taxonomies or controlled vocabularies, and will also introduce different software tools for doing so. Whether you need to create a taxonomy to organize information on a web site, classify information in a content management system, establish a controlled vocabulary for a periodical or database indexing project, or simply understand how to use them better, this workshop will get you on your way.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Students are expected to try out at least one demo version of thesaurus management software. Software is available for Windows, Mac (OS X 10.5 or later), and over the Web (any platform).</p>','online','2011-03-01','2011-03-31','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',0,0,0,0,1,'Information Organization',''),(3,'The Career-Savvy Information Professional','<p>Are you looking to get back into the library field and need some help getting up to date on all the new skills and trends? Are you interested in exploring different kinds of library careers, or looking to move beyond traditional library jobs? Have you recently entered the job market and are eager to learn ways you can stand out from the many other job applicants? Or would you just like to learn how to become a savvy career professional? If so, or if you\'d just like to be sure your skills are keeping up with new developments in the LIS field, then this workshop is for you.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As a participant in this workshop, you will build a personal career plan. First, learn how to assess your current skills and compare them with expectations in today\'s LIS job market; next, identify the transferable skills you bring to a desired position; and finally, create a plan to address any potential gaps.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Workshop topics will include career opportunities within all types of libraries, as well as alternatives to traditional library jobs. We will cover online career research tools and show ways you can structure and organize your career search process. We will also help you develop individualized strategies for updating your resume and new networking techniques to advance your career search, such as conducting effective informational interviews, researching and reaching out to employers, and broadening your professional network. Lastly, you will find out about a broad array of LIS professional development resources, including an optional workshop module that will help you develop and practice your skills with web 2.0 technologies.</p>','online','2010-10-01','2010-10-31','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','85','85',0,0,0,0,0,'Careers','Special pricing! Only $85 for all registrants!'),(4,'Writing for Publication','<p>The \"publish or perish\" syndrome is one of the most difficult aspects of academic life, especially for librarians, who often donâ€™t receive adequate support from their institutions. Besides the obvious benefits of promotion and tenure, publishing in academic journals can help make your work known within the library profession and lead to other projects, such as book contracts or further collaboration with professional colleagues. This course will teach you strategies and techniques that can help you get published. In the first part of the course, we will discuss the publishing cycle from article submission to the final step of signing an author contract. The second part of the course will focus on how to take an idea and develop it into a publishable article. Some of the topics addressed in this section will be: structuring an article to fit the style guide of a journal, the importance of doing a literature review, and strategies for time management and garnering institutional support. The last section of course will discuss strategies for getting work published. Some of the topics addressed will be: how to pick the right venue, why an article is accepted or rejected for publication, and how to rewrite an article to satisfy an editorâ€™s or a peer-reviewerâ€™s objections. Students are expected to have begun or to be thinking about an article-length work for publication.</p>','online','2011-06-01','2011-06-30','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',0,1,0,0,0,'Academic Libraries',''),(5,'Managing the One-Person Library','<p>Solo librarians, as well as assistant librarians and other paraprofessional library staff, will learn how to effectively and efficiently manage a one-person library of numerous types (e.g., academic, public, school) by learning operational, organizational, and marketing skills to ensure that their library grows, thrives, and becomes an integral part of their school and their community. They will also learn networking and professional development skills to enhance their experience and maintain their connections to the library community. Format will be weekly modules of reading assignments and written projects, with instructor assessment and student-instructor feedback and class participation. Students will be expected to actively participate in online discussions as an important complement to their written classwork.</p>','online','2011-04-01','2011-04-30','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',0,0,0,0,0,'Management',''),(6,'U.S. Private Company Research: More Sources Than You Think!','<p>Researching U.S. private companies is vitally important to information and business professionals in both private and nonprofit settings. While public companies are highly regulated, resulting in lots of information, U.S. private companies are not required to file financial or other information, with some exceptions, thus leaving fewer sources of information about them. Nevertheless, there are more sources than you think!  This course provides an extensive collection of resources used for researching U.S. private companies and includes sources that are rarely known to most researchers.  You\'ll learn effective and necessary search techniques for answering a range of different questions such as how to develop a financial picture when financials are not readily available, the importance of researching key executives and board members with methods for finding hard-to-find information about them, how to find and access suppliers, what\'s required for due diligence before doing business with a company or when considering a merger or acquisition - and more.  We\'ll discuss what the results or lack of results means and the next steps for digging more deeply using primary research techniques.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Expectations</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Participants will be expected to explore the tools and techniques provided in this workshop and conduct research about private companies of interest.  Regular participation in class discussion is requested for best results in creating a high-quality synergistic learning environment for all participants.</p>','online','2011-10-01','2011-10-31','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',0,1,0,0,0,'Reference/Research',''),(7,'MARC Basics for New Catalogers','<p>Although most new MLS graduates and experienced library staff members have been exposed to MARC records, creating and editing MARC bibliographic records as a Cataloger requires a greater familiarity with the format and standards. Understanding proper formatting is a key ingredient to creating searchable records in the online environment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This workshop will serve as an introduction (or basic refresher) to MARC21 Format for Bibliographic Data. It is intended for new catalogers and copy catalogers, as well as any library staff interested in learning more about MARC.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Topics will include: MARC terminology, identifying the elements of a bibliographic record, common MARC fields in a book record, common MARC fields in an audiovisual material record, and a discussion of the fluid nature of MARC. Participants will examine actual MARC records and create their own using a template. Assignments and quizzes will be completed on a weekly basis.</p>','online','2011-06-01','2011-06-30','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',0,1,0,0,0,'Information Organization',''),(8,'Secrets of Successful Youth Book Discussions','<p>In today\'s busy libraries, it\'s hard to find time to get away from the desk and lead a book discussion, and even harder for overextended children and young adults to make time in their schedules for library programs. How do you get started with this ambitious project? By the end of this session, participants will:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Discover best practices in book discussions for ages 10-18;</li>\r\n<li>Explore and evaluate different mediums for conducting book discussions (librarian led, round robin, blog, email discussion, bulletin board, instant messaging);</li>\r\n<li>Learn how to save time, money and energy by harnessing technology to create dynamic, interactive literary programs;</li>\r\n<li>Develop a discussion kit for one book (author bio, discussion questions, readalikes) to share with course participants.</li>\r\n</ul>','online','2010-10-01','2010-10-31','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',0,0,0,0,0,'Children\'s/YA/School Librarianship',NULL),(9,'Pop Culture in Libraries','<p>Students will be introduced to the important place pop culture has in libraries. Instructors will present on a variety of materials that should be a part of every library collection: books, films, music, comics, and new media. Through in person and online meetings, required reading and screenings, students will have a chance to learn about collection development, program planning, and satisfying the needs of their patrons by providing popular materials. Students will need to access streaming video online, audio, real time internet based chats, and in person participation.</p>','online','2010-10-01','2010-10-31','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',0,0,0,0,0,'Children\'s/YA/School Librarianship',NULL),(10,'They\'re Googling You: Online Identity for LIS Professionals','<p>Should you separate your professional online identity from the personal, and if so, how? Self-promotion and branding is becoming increasingly important as library professionals face dwindling traditional employment opportunities, due to layoffs, downsizing, budget cuts, and library closings. On a more positive note, library staff wishing to contribute back to the profession may want to hone a professional identity that makes one marketable for teaching and training purposes, conference speaking or consulting. Developing a professional online identity for either purpose may be a challenging and rewarding endeavor.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Through setting up a blog style website for personal/professional promotion, participants will:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Explore and evaluate online applications and social networking tools for professional development, self-promotion, and branding purposes</li>\r\n<li>Discuss identity and how you represent yourself professionally online</li>\r\n<li>Discover how to make yourself googleable</li>\r\n<li>Address online privacy and safety concerns</li>\r\n</ul>','online','2010-11-01','2010-11-30','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',1,0,0,0,0,'Careers',NULL),(11,'Graphic Novels for Adults and Academic Collections','<p>Graphic novels have now become staple collections for teens and children, but collections for adults and academic collections are becoming just as important.  If you\'re starting a new collection or want to solidify your understanding of this popular format for adults and students, this online course will illuminate the joys and challenges of collecting graphic novels and comics.  Over the month national graphic novel expert Robin Brenner will start by covering all of the basics of the format: what defines graphic novels, the history of comics and graphic novels, and who they\'re written for.  Then the class will progress through how to select them for your collection whether it be for adults or for academic study.  We will cover questions on how to justify a collection in these environments, how to justify and wisely select materials that may cause raised eyebrows in terms of adult content, and what kinds of genres exist for adults that selectors should be aware of in reading reviews.  Students will have a chance to read about and discuss programming, censorship and challenges, and cataloging related to graphic novels.  Every student should finish the month with an understanding of the format and how to start and/or maintain their collection. The online format encourages open discussion between students and teacher in discussing readings from both articles and graphic novels themselves, and weekly live chat sessions will be available for anyone who can attend the scheduled live discussions.  Everyone interested in this course should have access to a personal computer and the Internet and be able to navigate message boards, participate in chat sessions, and play mp3 files.</p>','online','2010-11-01','2010-11-30','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',1,0,0,0,0,'Academic Libraries',NULL),(12,'Keeping Up With New Technologies, While Keeping Your Sanity','<p>How often do you hear about a new web tool, or a \"tech\" development and you don\'t have any idea what it\'s about? Do you sometimes wish you knew a little more about what some of the tools do, and how they can relate to libraries? This workshop will provide some basic information on recent developments in the \"techie\" world of web tools, and how to incorporate them into your existing work. Topics will include creating your own RSS feeds for sharing information, understanding mashups, and strategies for keeping up in this ever-changing environment. Students will learn about the topics through readings, online discussions and practical application of tools, and will complete the workshop with a realistic plan for keeping up to date with new developments in libraries and beyond.  This workshop is tailored for people who don\'t have much experience with 2.0 tools, or those who are looking for a way to get familiar with emerging technologies.  No prior technological experience necessary -- just a willingness to learn!</p>','online','2010-11-01','2010-11-30','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',0,0,0,0,0,'Technology/Web 2.0',NULL),(13,'Winning Library Grants','<p>In these difficult economic times, seeking grants is more important than ever for librarians. Grants may be the only way you can address the changing needs in your community while your library budget is flat or shrinking. This course will introduce you to the grant process from beginning to end with an emphasis on planning successful grant projects, funding sources for libraries, researching grant opportunities, proposal basics, and grant-winning tips and techniques useful for all types of libraries and grant types. Course modules are designed to follow the instructorâ€™s Grant Process Cycle model, which illustrates how grant work is an ongoing holistic process that can be integrated into your jobs as librarians. You will not learn to write grants in this workshop but it will prepare you for the Writing Successful Grant Proposals workshop.</p>','online','2010-11-01','2010-11-30','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',0,0,0,0,0,'Management',NULL),(14,'Redefining Reluctant Readers','<p>What counts as reading? Who decides--the reader or the observer? In this workshop, participants will examine definitions and societal beliefs about reading, literacy, and literary formats. In the educational sector, it has long been agreed that varying learning styles exist, and yet, \"alternative\" formats such as audio books and graphic novels continue to be dismissed and not considered \"reading.\" Participants will explore these issues and learn ways to redefine, reach, and \"turn into readers\" even the most reluctant patrons and students in their libraries and schools. Through literature surveys in multiple formats, research articles, and prolific discussion, common pitfalls will be replaced with immediately implementable marketing, collection development, reader\'s advisory, and programming ideas for tweens and teens (as well as adults) previously labeled as \"non-readers.\" Resources will be provided by the instructor and collaborative lists will be built over the course of this four week workshop designed to redefine reluctant readers and the way libraries and schools serve their needs.</p>','online','2010-11-01','2010-11-30','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',0,0,0,0,0,'Children\'s/YA/School Librarianship',''),(15,'Strategic Information Arrangement','<p>Arranged information creates an opportunity to persuade, but to earn that opportunity, you first must understand the basic structures of arrangement design.  \"Strategic Information Arrangement\" takes an entertaining look at arrangement strategies and persuasive opportunities found in hierarchical taxonomy, classification, and structured lists.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You learn the persuasive techniques of Stanfordâ€™s B. J. Fogg.  You discover how each arrangement method fits a unique purpose and how to persuasively exploit these strategies.  Katherine\'s client Snoopy is on hand to explain some of the concepts. Nevadaâ€™s Burning Man art festival and the Rolling Stones make appearances.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We also review the powerful name arrangement at the Vietnam Veterans Memorial, demonstrating six of Foggâ€™s seven persuasive strategies.  The Memorial to the Missing of the Somme from World War I had similar information and goals to the VVM.  Yet the distinct characteristics of the two wars require entirely different name arrangement strategies.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the course, you will be invited to describe memorials in your local area, for possible inclusion in <a href=\"http://isisinblog.typepad.com/isisinblog/2010/11/memorials-for-veterans-day-discovered-by-the-simmons-strategic-information-arrangement-class-novembe.html\">Katherineâ€™s Memorial Day posting</a>.  You can also design your own hierarchic structure with provided material on an entertaining subject.  These optional assignments are critiqued by Katherine, the only information strategist focused on persuasive arrangement.</p>','online','2011-05-01','2011-05-31','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',0,1,0,0,0,'Information Organization',''),(16,'Extending Mobile Library Services with QR Codes','<p>Are you looking to extend and develop your library\'s mobile services? QR codes offer many easily implementable and affordable opportunities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This workshop will examine:</p>\r\n \r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The basics of QR codes - what are they and how they work</li>\r\n<li>How QR codes are being used around the world to link together people, knowledge, and physical locations</li>\r\n<li>How to build QR code applications for your library</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n \r\n<p>Workshop participants will leave the course with a solid understanding of the basics and mechanics of QR codes and 20 easy ways to implement QR codes in their libraries and/or communities. All Course participants will select and complete a simple QR code course project which will give them practical experience working with QR codes.</p>','online','2011-03-01','2011-03-31','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',0,0,0,0,0,'Technology/Web 2.0',''),(17,'Digital Copyright','<p>This four-week workshop gives students a hands-on, nonacademic view of copyright. Bring your own real-life scenarios for class discussion. Who owns the works I create? When can I use text, images and music created by others? Learn how to determine if an item is in the public domain. If it is not, learn how to determine if the library/archive or another user exception in copyright law allows your use. If the user exceptions don\'t fit your need, learn how to make a good faith Fair Use evaluation. Finally, learn some tips about getting permission to use others\' works.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Assignments include: registering for a copyright, creating a creative commons license for a work you\'ve created, searching the Copyright Clearance Center (<a href=\"http://www.copyright.com/\">copyright.com</a>) for permissions and designating a copyright agent with the Copyright Office (optional).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Threaded discussions with classmates and the instructor will be the primary means of teaching.</p>','online','2011-04-01','2011-04-30','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',0,0,0,0,0,'Technology/Web 2.0',''),(18,'Periodical/Database Indexing','<p>Ever wanted to know more about indexing magazines, journals, newsletters, or newspapers?  Have you wondered how databases index periodicals? This online workshop will provide a comprehensive introduction to periodical/database indexing including the basic principles of indexing all types of periodicals, how to develop a small controlled vocabulary appropriate for the issues of a single journal title, as well as the similarities and differences in indexing for a database. Also included will be some suggestions on ways to get started in periodical/database indexing.</p>','online','2011-10-01','2011-11-12','00:00:00','00:00:00','25','275','220',0,1,0,0,0,'Information Organization',''),(19,'Taxonomies and Controlled Vocabularies','<p><a href=\"http://www.hedden-information.com/GSLIS-taxonomies.htm\">Preview this workshop.</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Taxonomies are becoming popular for organizing information in business knowledge management, enterprise content management systems, and intranets. Are these taxonomies different from literature retrieval thesauri? How does one go about creating a taxonomy? This online workshop will provide recommended best practices for how to create terms, relationships, and variants for different kinds of taxonomies or controlled vocabularies, and will also introduce different software tools for doing so. Whether you need to create a taxonomy to organize information on a web site, classify information in a content management system, establish a controlled vocabulary for a periodical or database indexing project, or simply understand how to use them better, this workshop will get you on your way.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Students are expected to try out at least one demo version of thesaurus management software. Software is available for Windows, Mac (OS X 10.5 or later), and over the Web (any platform).</p>','online','2011-01-04','2011-02-04','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',0,0,0,0,1,'Information Organization',''),(20,'Marketing Your Library','<p>What exactly is marketing and what does your library need to do it right? Money? A marketing plan? A dedicated job position? No, no, and no! Marketing does not have to eat up your budget (sometimes, it even saves money); you donâ€™t have to devote an entire job position to it; and you certainly donâ€™t need a lengthy marketing plan. Marketing is the process of communicating with users and potential users to determine their needs; designing services to meet those needs; and informing users about your services. This workshop will introduce students to basic marketing definitions and concepts, but the main focus will be on developing a user-centered approach to marketing that can be customized to studentsâ€™ individual libraries. The class will draw on marketing lessons learned from outside the library world as well as proven marketing successes in public, academic, and special libraries (case studies will be presented on a weekly basis).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In this workshop, participants will:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Learn the basics of the marketing cycle</li>\r\n<li>Apply concepts of product lines and market segmentation to their own libraries</li>\r\n<li>Discover various techniques for gathering information about library users</li>\r\n<li>Identify metrics to tell a compelling story about the impact of your library</li>\r\n<li>Explore library marketing trends, such as word-of-mouth marketing, value studies, design thinking, and ethnographic studies</li>\r\n<li>Receive peer and instructor feedback on a promotional idea or plan</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>â€œGood pace, great resources that can be taken away and referenced later, great feedback from workshop leader.â€ â€“student, 2010 â€œMarketing Your Libraryâ€ workshop</p>','online','2011-03-01','2011-03-31','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',0,0,0,0,0,'Management',''),(21,'Managing and Growing Youth Services Collections in the Digital Age','<p>As the world becomes increasingly mobile and a digital, are you looking for new ways to increase the accessibility of your materials, your perceived value, your use, your circulation, and build your collections? Are you looking for ways to actively engage more children and families and build a broader sense of community within your locale?</p>\r\n \r\n<p>During this course we will look at youth collections and examine:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Physical collections, layouts, and organization</li>\r\n<li>Digital collections and broadening their availability to users</li>\r\n<li>Mobile knowledge, mobile devices, and mobile services</li>\r\n<li>People\'s changing patterns of information-seeking and community interaction</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Participants will leave with practical, affordable, and easily implementable ways to manage, market, enhance their youth collections to engage and connect with a larger audience. This course is geared toward public libraries.</p>','online','2011-01-04','2011-02-04','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',0,0,0,0,0,'Children\'s/YA/School Librarianship',''),(22,'Technology Programming for Teens','<p>Jump onto the Web 2.0 bandwagon by offering interactive, multimedia content creation programs for teens at the library!  Discover model programs in technology for teens while experimenting with new technologies and evaluating for usability.  Discuss the benefits and barriers to delivering tech programs for teens, and learn how to justify and then replicate these inexpensive and easy tech programs for teens in your library.  By the end of this session, participants will: make an avatar; discover how to use Wordle; test a video game designed by teens, and create their own; chat with an author via instant messaging; participate in a book review podcast; and brainstorm a teen technology program to implement at their library.</p>','online','2011-01-04','2011-02-04','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',0,0,0,1,0,'Children\'s/YA/School Librarianship',''),(23,'Secrets of Successful Searching for School Librarians','<p>School librarians must find high quality information and teach K-12 students how to answer questions for assignments.  While everyone searches Google, few have learned all the advanced search techniques.  Open your eyes to the greater possibilities of finding answers to complex questions in this workshop conducted by an outstanding Internet research authority. While Google is an excellent search engine, itâ€™s rarely used to best advantage. Expert researcher Amelia Kassel will bring you to the next level of finding information for student assignments about science, health, technology, environmental issues and more.  Beyond discovering how to get the most from Google, you will be introduced to specialty search engines and government sources just for kids.  Join with your school librarian colleagues to exchange ideas about what works, doesnâ€™t work and how to find quality information with not only the best sources but also techniques you can teach to your students.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"font-weight:bold\">Expectations</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Participants will be expected to explore the tools and techniques provided in this workshop and conduct research on topics they select based on specific interests and needs. Regular participation in class discussion is requested for best results in creating a high-quality synergistic learning environment for all participants.</p>','online','2011-02-01','2011-02-28','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',1,0,0,0,0,'Reference/Research',NULL),(24,'Creating Web Site Indexes','<p>As websites grow in size and complexity, users need additional means beyond the navigational menu and a site map to search a site for the information they want.  Unless a site is very large, an onsite search engine often does not retrieve satisfactory results.  Browsable A-Z indexes, on the other hand, a format familiar to users from their appearance at the back of nonfiction books, can provide highly accurate retrieval when added to websites.  Index entries are hyperlinked to the desired text within a webpage or to an anchored point such as the section heading within the webpage.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>During this workshop, participants will learn how to create and format a hyperlinked A-Z website index and how to use a freeware web indexing tool and the free demo of another web indexing tool.  The workshop begins with a discussion about the structure of a website index and which sites would benefit from an index.  Topics covered include basic skills in indexing, the process of indexing, and the use of HTML code in indexing.  Basic knowledge of either HTML or HTML editors (such as Dreamweaver or Microsoft FrontPage) is assumed.  Prior training or experience in indexing is not required, but would be helpful.  Participants will need a computer running Windows (to run the web indexing tools), Internet access, a web browser, and e-mail.</p>','online','2011-02-01','2011-02-28','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',0,0,0,0,0,'Information Organization',''),(25,'The Career-Savvy Information Professional','<p>Are you looking to get back into the library field and need some help getting up to date on all the new skills and trends? Are you interested in exploring different kinds of library careers, or looking to move beyond traditional library jobs? Have you recently entered the job market and are eager to learn ways you can stand out from the many other job applicants? Or would you just like to learn how to become a savvy career professional? If so, or if you\'d just like to be sure your skills are keeping up with new developments in the LIS field, then this workshop is for you.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As a participant in this workshop, you will build a personal career plan. First, learn how to assess your current skills and compare them with expectations in today\'s LIS job market; next, identify the transferable skills you bring to a desired position; and finally, create a plan to address any potential gaps.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Workshop topics will include career opportunities within all types of libraries, as well as alternatives to traditional library jobs. We will cover online career research tools and show ways you can structure and organize your career search process. We will also help you develop individualized strategies for updating your resume and new networking techniques to advance your career search, such as conducting effective informational interviews, researching and reaching out to employers, and broadening your professional network. Lastly, you will find out about a broad array of LIS professional development resources, including an optional workshop module that will help you develop and practice your skills with web 2.0 technologies.</p>','online','2011-02-01','2011-02-28','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','85','85',0,0,0,0,0,'Careers','Special pricing! Only $85 for all registrants!'),(26,'Isn\'t Otaku a Kind of Sushi?  Graphic Novels, Manga and Anime','<p>Join graphic novel, manga and anime enthusiast (and librarian) Robin Brenner for a look into the world of graphic novels, Japanese manga (print comics), and anime (animation). Learn about the history of the art form, the elements that make it unique, where to find more information, how to understand and attract fans and new readers, how to create programming ideas and opportunities, and how to build the best collections for libraries. This workshop will concentrate on core collections and new titles as well as highlighting the latest trends in Japanese manga and anime, the top selling titles with teens. Participants will need a computer with Internet access, e-mail, and the ability to open Powerpoint, PDF, and audio files such as mp4 from iTunes or mp3.</p>','online','2011-02-01','2011-02-28','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',0,0,0,0,0,'Children\'s/YA/School Librarianship',NULL),(27,'Business Research 101: Sources and Strategies','<p>If you work or plan to work in a corporate, academic or public library that provides any kind of business reference service or if you do business research for yourself, this class is for you. Over four weeks we will cover basic sources and strategies in the areas of company, industry, international business, and marketing research. Sources explored in the course will include major free web resources, such as Edgar, the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission\'s free database, the governmentâ€™s Bureau of Economic Analysis, Reuters\' database for company information, and Eurostat, a great source for international statistics and business information. We will also look at subscription business databases.  The workshop will include trial logins from Mergent Online and Plunkett Research Online. Students will work on various research examples to gain a good understanding of how to tackle basic business research questions typically found in library work and will be able to share their experience of sources covered in the course with colleagues via the discussion list. Students will also focus on a short research project of particular interest to them and complete it over the course of the four weeks. A bibliography of further reading in business research will be made available via the course. Time commitment: approximately 15 hours total or about 3.75 hours per week.</p>','online','2011-02-01','2011-02-28','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',0,0,0,0,0,'Reference/Research',''),(28,'Instructional Design: Creating Effective Materials for Online Learning','<p>What is instructional design and why is it important in the development of online learning materials? And what is the role of instructional technology in the design process? Technology tools abound. Wikis, blogs, podcasts, asynchronous and synchronous forums have become popular and are tempting instructors to say, \"We need to develop a wiki,\" or \"We need to be podcasting,\" rather than purposefully looking at the instructional need first.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At the end of this course, you will have a basic understanding of instructional design principles as they pertain to online learning. You will be able to apply instructional design principles to solve online instructional challenges. You will also identify the role technologies play in the design process and how to determine which tool works best for what purpose, but most importantly, you will develop skills essential to preparing an online course or online tutorial.</p>','online','2011-02-01','2011-02-28','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',0,0,0,0,0,'User Instruction/Information Literacy',NULL),(29,'Creative Writing Programs for Youth','<p>Libraries celebrate the written word in a myriad of ways; writing workshops for youth ages 8-18 is just one. If you\'ve always wanted to host a creative writing workshop or poetry slam, are curious about digital storytelling, or just need to answer a child\'s reference request for places that publish youth writing, this workshop, presented just in time to launch a program during National Poetry Month in April 2011, is for you! By the end of this session, participants will:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Share online and print resources for creative writing program planning;</li>\r\n<li>Try a number of simple writing exercises to replicate with youth;</li>\r\n<li>Identify model writing programs, including contests, literary magazines, and standalone sessions;</li>\r\n<li>Get tips for how to teach youth how to edit, present and deliver feedback on one another\'s writing.</li>\r\n</ul>','online','2011-02-01','2011-02-28','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',1,0,0,0,0,'Children\'s/YA/School Librarianship',NULL),(30,'Secrets of Successful Searching for Business, Public, and Academic Librarians','<p>Librarians in various settings must find and teach users how to answer questions.  While everyone searches Google, few have learned all the advanced search techniques.  Open your eyes to the greater possibilities of finding answers to complex questions in this workshop conducted by an outstanding Internet research authority. While Google is an excellent search engine, itâ€™s rarely used to best advantage. Expert researcher Amelia Kassel will bring you to the next level of finding information for questions about business, science, health, technology, environmental issues and more.  Beyond discovering how to get the most from Google, you will be introduced to specialty search engines, government sources, and methods for finding hard-to-find information on the deep web using dynamic search tools that many are not yet familiar with.  Join with your colleagues to exchange ideas about what works, doesnâ€™t work and how to find quality information with not only the best sources for finding answers but also techniques you can teach end users.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"font-weight:bold\">Expectations</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Participants will be expected to explore the tools and techniques provided in this workshop and conduct research on topics they select based on specific interests and needs. Regular participation in class discussion is requested for best results in creating a high-quality synergistic learning environment for all participants.</p>','online','2011-03-01','2011-03-31','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',1,0,0,0,0,'Reference/Research',NULL),(31,'Building a Website with WordPress','<p>WordPress is not just for blogs.  It can be used to create a dynamic website for your public library with little to no programming knowledge.  In this hands-on workshop, participants will create a free account with WordPress in order to practice using the software.  Topics will include a review of how WordPress works, creating posts and pages, inserting images and other media, and customizing a blog with widgets and plugins that can add content such as calendars, RSS feeds, images, and instant messaging (IM).</p>','holyoke','2011-04-10','2011-04-10','13:30:00','17:00:00','3.5','160','125',0,0,0,0,0,'Technology/Web 2.0',''),(32,'Artists\' Books','<p>Register for more than one workshop <a href=\"bookarts.php\">in this series</a> to receive a discount.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Artists\' Books have become more prevalent and collectible over the past 20 years, and they\'re showing up in more and more library rare book collections.  This full-day course will help you make sense of the many varieties of philosophical, artistic, and historical perspectives book artists and their work have come from.  Through slide lectures and physical examples, we will cover the materials, methods, and sources used by artists, as well as galleries, libraries, and other resources available to the researcher and budding artist.</p>','simmons','2010-09-25','2010-09-25','09:00:00','17:00:00','7','220','175',1,0,0,1,0,'Book Arts & Artists\' Books: A Workshop Series',''),(33,'Identifying and Caring for your Audio-Visual Materials','<p>This workshop is for archivists and librarians with little to no experience working with magnetic audio-visual material. The format will be a PowerPoint presentation mixed with a hands on exercise in identifying a variety of media that one would typically find in their collection. In this interactive workshop, students will learn the history of magnetic media, what magnetic tape is made of, the types of deterioration and what they look like, proper storage, reformatting options and the emergence of JPEG2000 and the concept of \"The Preservation Factory\". The instructor strongly encourages students to bring examples of magnetic media from their collection if they have specific questions.</p>','simmons','2010-10-02','2010-10-02','09:00:00','17:00:00','7','220','175',0,0,0,0,0,'Archives',NULL),(34,'Bookmaking for the Beginner 1','<p>Whether you\'re interested in making books as art, making blank journals, or just curious about bookbinding, this course will help you understand the basic principles of a book\'s construction and function.  Topics to be covered in discussion and with hands-on work are:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Paper - how to choose and work with different kinds (folding, cutting, determining grain, direction)</li>\r\n<li>Adhesives - what different adhesives do as well as when and how to use them</li>\r\n<li>Sewing - choosing threads and needles as well as various sewing techniques and tips</li>\r\n<li>Structure - how structures work, what their strengths and weaknesses are, and how to decide on a structure which complements the book\'s content</li>\r\n<li>Proportion - page size and shape and the thickness of the book</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>You will construct models of these basic binding structures: one sheet fold-up (the flutter book or ox-plow), other simple folded structures, accordion, single section pamphlet, two section pamphlet and chain link stitch, and multi-section.</p>','simmons','2011-04-02','2011-04-02','09:00:00','17:00:00','7','220','175',0,0,0,0,0,'Book Arts & Artists\' Books: A Workshop Series','Part of <a href=\"http://alanis.simmons.edu/ceweb/bookarts.php\">Book Arts & Artists Books: A Workshop Series</a>'),(35,'Practical Tagging and Keyword Invention','<p>Knowing how to control a vocabulary is important, but what if you don\'t have a vocabulary? This workshop provides participants with a simple algorithm for inventing all those words you forgot to invent last time, along with several practical examples, followed by critical suggestions on where and how to apply them. Whether you\'re an indexer looking to lengthen your index, or a website owner looking to get more Google hits, you\'ll appreciate a fast, fresh look at words, words, words.</p>','online','2010-10-23','2010-10-23','09:00:00','17:00:00','7','220','175',0,0,0,0,0,'Information Organization',NULL),(36,'Mother Goose on the Loose','<p>After a brief review of theories of learning based on findings in brain research, you will participate in a hands-on program! Hear about the structure of Mother Goose on the Loose and how it combines language, books, illustration, music, movement, drama, and creative interaction to create an optimal learning environment. Experience program songs and rhymes created by Canadian music educator, Barbara Cass-Beggs. Connect the program components with best practices for developing school readiness skills. Make flannel board pieces to keep. Learn how to incorporate all this into your own early childhood programs with a step-by-step guide to planning and executing your program.</p>','simmons','2011-07-23','2011-07-23','09:00:00','15:30:00','5','195','155',0,1,0,0,0,'Children\'s/YA/School Librarianship',''),(37,'Letterpress: History, Process, and Printing','<p>Register for more than one workshop <a href=\"bookarts.php\">in this series</a> to receive a discount.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Letterpress printing is experiencing a new resurgence in graphic design as well as artists\' books.  Through slides and discussion learn how the process works, its changes and advances over the last 600 years.  Also learn about the work of present-day artists and what visual and tactile possibilities letterpress printing has.  This full-day workshop will consist of slide lecture, discussion, and hands-on experience with physical examples as well as printing a small keepsake on a table-top platen press.  We will also discuss resources for further learning and the setting up of one\'s own shop..</p>','online','2010-11-13','2010-11-13','09:00:00','17:00:00','7','220','175',1,0,0,0,0,'Book Arts & Artists\' Books: A Workshop Series',NULL),(38,'Pop-up Books','<p>Remember some of your favorite pop-up books from when you were a kid?  Or do you work in a rare book library where you\'ve come across some surprisingly old books with pop-up parts?  Well, if you\'ve often wondered how these structures work and where they come from, this workshop will help you understand some of the basic ideas behind the history and production of pop-up books.  After a discussion and slide talk covering the history of pop-up books, be ready for some hands-on exploration of some basic pop-up structures, including making a few examples of your own.</p>','simmons','2011-06-11','2011-06-12','09:00:00','17:00:00','14','395','315',1,1,0,0,0,'Book Arts & Artists\' Books: A Workshop Series','Workshop runs from 9:00am - 5:00pm both days<br />Part of <a href=\"http://alanis.simmons.edu/ceweb/bookarts.php\">Book Arts & Artists Books: A Workshop Series</a>'),(40,'Zotero','<p><a href=\"http://zotero.org/\">Zotero</a> is a free, open-source reference manager for librarians and researchers of any level, from high school student through university faculty. It takes advantage of the best features of both desktop and cloud applications to turn the Firefox web browser into a powerful research tool. In this course, an experienced instructor will take you from zero Zotero knowledge to Zotero master.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Through hands-on activities, reading, and discussion, participants in this course will:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Week 1: Install, learn, and use Zotero. Create your personal library and explore how it works. Create bibliographies for word processors or the web. Discuss how your students or users might benefit from Zotero.</li>\r\n<li>Week 2: Store your Zotero library in the cloud to access it from any computer. Use group libraries to collaborate, share, and publish resources.</li>\r\n<li>Week 3: Examine and discuss best practices for teaching and supporting Zotero in the library.</li>\r\n<li>Week 4: Learn and discuss tips, tricks, hacks, and advanced techniques. Share your final project: create a practical application for teaching or using Zotero in your own library.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Prerequisites: Participants must use the <a href=\"http://www.mozilla.com/en-US/firefox/personal.html\">Firefox web browser</a> and either Microsoft Word or Open Office. No technical skills beyond basic computer literacy are assumed.</p>','online','2011-03-01','2011-03-31','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',1,0,0,0,0,'Reference/Research',''),(41,'Google Apps: Improving Communication, Productivity, and Searching','<p>Google is now more than just a search engine. Google offers a range of applications which improve communication, productivity, and for searching the web. This workshop will explore several of Google\'s free applications including Google Docs, Google Sites, iGoogle, Google Calendar, and custom searches and discuss how these tools will not only help you become more productive personally but how they can add value to existing and future library services. The first week of this workshop explore applications that participants can use to improve their personal productivity and organization. The second week of this workshop will explore different office applications. The final two weeks of this workshop will discuss how Google applications can be used in your library to improve existing services or offer new services to connect, communicate, and work with your user population. As part of this workshop, participants will need an existing or create a new Google account.</p>','online','2011-03-01','2011-03-31','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',0,0,0,0,0,'Technology/Web 2.0',NULL),(42,'Apps4Librarians: Becoming an Expert in Mobile Apps for iPhones, iPads, and Other iOS Devices','<p>In today\'s world of increased use of smartphones and mobile devices, we are seeing an explosion of mobile apps and mobile web sites for productivity, information research, reading, and studying. Librarians have an opportunity to serve their communities by combining their content knowledge with expertise in mobile technologies.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In this course you\'ll learn about the best apps available on the iOS platform in categories of interest to library users for research, productivity, writing, reading, and multimedia. Some apps we\'ll cover include Evernote, Dropbox, Instapaper, iBooks, Kindle, Stanza, GoodReader, and more.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Each week we\'ll focus on a different category of app, such as e-reading, productivity, writing, or multimedia. The course will combine video lectures, reading, discussion, and your real-world experience. We will also discuss the ongoing debates about the future of apps vs. mobile web, and content consumption vs. content creation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To participate, you\'ll need to have at least one of the following: iPhone, iPod Touch, or iPad. We are focusing on the iOS platform since stats show highest use (in the U.S.) of that mobile platform currently.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Students will be asked to write their own reviews to share with the class, either written or in video format (your choice). By the end of the class you should have enough material to offer a workshop of your own for your library users or staff.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For more information, see <a href=\"http://apps4librarians.com/\">http://apps4librarians.com/</a>.</p>','online','2011-06-01','2011-07-12','00:00:00','00:00:00','25','275','220',0,1,0,0,0,'Technology/Web 2.0','Please note: This is a six-week workshop.'),(44,'Taxonomies and Controlled Vocabularies','<p><a href=\"http://www.hedden-information.com/GSLIS-taxonomies.htm\">Preview this workshop.</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Taxonomies are becoming popular for organizing information in business knowledge management, enterprise content management systems, and intranets. Are these taxonomies different from literature retrieval thesauri? How does one go about creating a taxonomy? This online workshop will provide recommended best practices for how to create terms, relationships, and variants for different kinds of taxonomies or controlled vocabularies, and will also introduce different software tools for doing so. Whether you need to create a taxonomy to organize information on a web site, classify information in a content management system, establish a controlled vocabulary for a periodical or database indexing project, or simply understand how to use them better, this workshop will get you on your way.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Students are expected to try out at least one demo version of thesaurus management software. Software is available for Windows, Mac (OS X 10.5 or later), and over the Web (any platform).</p>','online','2011-05-01','2011-05-31','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',0,1,0,0,1,'Information Organization','<a href=\"http://alanis.simmons.edu/ceweb/workshop.php?id=62\">September</a> and <a href=\"http://alanis.simmons.edu/ceweb/workshop.php?id=63\">November</a> have seats available.'),(46,'Video Tutorials: When, Why, and How to Use Them','<p>Video tutorials are a great tool for reaching your users and grabbing their attention. In this workshop, we will look at best practices for tutorials and then apply those to tutorials used by libraries in both public and academic settings. Then, participants will learn about the tools available (even on the cheap) that can be used to create tutorials for marketing, teaching, demonstrating processes and more. Participants will have hands on time to practice storyboarding and creating tutorials.</p>','simmons','2011-04-30','2011-04-30','09:00:00','17:00:00','7','220','175',0,0,0,0,0,'User Instruction/Information Literacy',''),(45,'Taxonomies and Controlled Vocabularies','<p><a href=\"http://www.hedden-information.com/GSLIS-taxonomies.htm\">Preview this workshop.</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Taxonomies are becoming popular for organizing information in business knowledge management, enterprise content management systems, and intranets. Are these taxonomies different from literature retrieval thesauri? How does one go about creating a taxonomy? This online workshop will provide recommended best practices for how to create terms, relationships, and variants for different kinds of taxonomies or controlled vocabularies, and will also introduce different software tools for doing so. Whether you need to create a taxonomy to organize information on a web site, classify information in a content management system, establish a controlled vocabulary for a periodical or database indexing project, or simply understand how to use them better, this workshop will get you on your way.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Students are expected to try out at least one demo version of thesaurus management software. Software is available for Windows, Mac (OS X 10.5 or later), and over the Web (any platform).</p>','online','2011-07-01','2011-07-31','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',0,1,0,0,1,'Information Organization','<a href=\"http://alanis.simmons.edu/ceweb/workshop.php?id=62\">September</a> and <a href=\"http://alanis.simmons.edu/ceweb/workshop.php?id=63\">November</a> have seats available.'),(47,'Digitization Strategies, Technologies, and Practices','<p>Libraries  and  archives  are  digitizing  materials  or  planning  digitization  projects  for  many  reasons: for  use  in  instruction,  for  archival  and  preservation  purposes,  and  for  public  showcase.  Setting up  a  digitization project  or  function  involves  many  decisions  and  can  be  overwhelming  with  questions  about  equipment, best  practices,  staffing  resources,  technologies,  and  standards.  Participants  in  this  workshop  will  learn how  to  plan,  design,  and  implement  the  digitization  processes.  Topics  to  be  covered  include:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Digitization Environment\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Creating a central digitization function</li>\r\n<li>Planning and managing digitization projects</li>\r\n<li>Project selection and scoping</li>\r\n<li>Staffing and skill sets</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n\r\n<li>Equipment\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Analog to digital</li>\r\n<li>Choosing the right equipment, hardware and software</li>\r\n<li>Operating digitization equipment</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n\r\n<li>Fine Tuning\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Digital file management and storage/infrastructure</li>\r\n<li>Establishing workflow and automation</li>\r\n<li>Digital technology standards</li>\r\n<li>Digital collections standards</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n\r\n<li>\r\nResources\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Funding sources</li>\r\n<li>Outsourcing and vendor selection</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>','holyoke','2011-03-12','2011-03-12','09:00:00','17:00:00','7','220','175',0,0,0,0,0,'Archives',''),(49,'Managing and Growing Youth Services Collections in the Digital Age','<p>As the world becomes increasingly mobile and a digital, are you looking for new ways to increase the accessibility of your materials, your perceived value, your use, your circulation, and build your collections? Are you looking for ways to actively engage more children and families and build a broader sense of community within your locale?</p>\r\n \r\n<p>During this course we will look at youth collections and examine:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Physical collections, layouts, and organization</li>\r\n<li>Digital collections and broadening their availability to users</li>\r\n<li>Mobile knowledge, mobile devices, and mobile services</li>\r\n<li>People\'s changing patterns of information-seeking and community interaction</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Participants will leave with practical, affordable, and easily implementable ways to manage, market, enhance their youth collections to engage and connect with a larger audience. This course is geared toward public libraries.</p>','online','2011-07-01','2011-07-31','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',0,1,0,0,0,'Children\'s/YA/School Librarianship',''),(62,'Taxonomies and Controlled Vocabularies','<p><a href=\"http://www.hedden-information.com/GSLIS-taxonomies.htm\">Preview this workshop.</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Taxonomies are becoming popular for organizing information in business knowledge management, enterprise content management systems, and intranets. Are these taxonomies different from literature retrieval thesauri? How does one go about creating a taxonomy? This online workshop will provide recommended best practices for how to create terms, relationships, and variants for different kinds of taxonomies or controlled vocabularies, and will also introduce different software tools for doing so. Whether you need to create a taxonomy to organize information on a web site, classify information in a content management system, establish a controlled vocabulary for a periodical or database indexing project, or simply understand how to use them better, this workshop will get you on your way.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Students are expected to try out at least one demo version of thesaurus management software. Software is available for Windows, Mac (OS X 10.5 or later), and over the Web (any platform).</p>','online','2011-09-01','2011-09-30','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',0,1,0,0,0,'Information Organization',''),(48,'Genealogy Information Services','<p>This four-week online workshop will prepare students to provide library and archival services to genealogists. Students will acquire a practical knowledge of genealogical users and resources and explore related topics including reference, cataloging, collection development, outreach, and professional development.</p>','online','2011-08-01','2011-08-31','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',0,1,0,0,0,'Reference/Research',''),(50,'Business Research 102: Business Ethics','<p>This class will help you develop your skills in the vital area of business ethics research.  Over four weeks we will cover basic sources and strategies in the areas of accounting ethics, corporate culture, responsibility and sustainability, banking and ethical investment, and business law. Sources explored in the course will include major free web resources, such as Financial Accounting Standards Board, Edgar, the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission\'s free database, FindLaw, \" \"The Federal Register, The Better Business Bureau, the State Securities Regulators, American Bankers Association, National Labor Relations Board, Federal Insurance Deposit Corporation, Reuters and many more. We will also look at subscription business databases and if possible, students will find and explore these via local libraries. Students will work on various research examples to gain a good understanding of how to tackle basic and more advanced business research questions in the above areas related to business ethics, typically found in library work and will be able to share their experience of sources covered in the course with colleagues via the discussion list. Students will also focus on a short research project of particular interest to them and complete it over the course of the four weeks. A bibliography of further reading in business research will be made available via the workshop. Time commitment: approximately 15 hours total or about 3.75 hours per week.</p>','online','2011-08-01','2011-08-31','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',0,1,0,0,0,'Reference/Research',''),(51,'Information Literacy: Assessing for Change','<p>This course is for librarians who may be doing instruction but would like to get a sense of what their patrons need to learn and whether they are actually learning from library instruction. This course will focus on methods of assessment and evaluation for both teacher and learner. Participants will learn how to create a needs assessment, assess patron learning and evaluate the effectiveness of their instruction.</p>','online','2011-08-01','2011-08-31','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',1,1,0,0,0,'User Instruction/Information Literacy',''),(52,'Technology Grants for Libraries','<p>Todayâ€™s libraries are more dependent than ever on technology to deliver information and provide information access to the people we serve. Despite an increased demand for technology in libraries, many library budgets have remained flat or have even been cut in recent years. Grants are one way you can address this challenge. This course will introduce you to the grant process from beginning to end with an emphasis on planning successful technology grant projects, technology funding sources for libraries, researching grant opportunities, proposal basics, and grant-winning tips and techniques useful for all types of libraries. Course modules are designed to illustrate that grant work is an ongoing process that can be integrated into your jobs as librarians.</p>','online','2011-07-01','2011-07-31','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',1,1,0,0,0,'Management',''),(53,'Bookmaking for the Beginner 2','<p>For those interested in expanding on what they learned in the Bookbinding 1 workshop, this workshop explores more multi-section books and sewing techniques. Structures included will be supported sewings, such as long stitch and sewing on tapes; exposed sewings, such as the Coptic binding and the Secret Belgian Binding. Some basic pop-ups structures may also be covered.</p>','simmons','2011-05-07','2011-05-07','09:00:00','17:00:00','7','220','175',1,1,0,0,0,'Book Arts & Artists\' Books: A Workshop Series','Part of <a href=\"http://alanis.simmons.edu/ceweb/bookarts.php\">Book Arts & Artists Books: A Workshop Series</a>'),(54,'Print Methods for the Collector and Conservator','<p>This course is designed for framers, paper conservators, book conservators, preservation specialists, and all other paper enthusiasts. Through lectures and examples, this course will cover the processes of intaglio (etching, aquatint, mezzotint, drypoint, engraving, etc.), wood cut, wood engraving, process line and halftone relief, lithography, monoprinting, screenprinting, and more. By viewing these techniques through video and examples and learning the telltale marks each process leaves, students will gain the ability to identify, and thus properly handle, the types of prints they encounter in their field.</p>','simmons','2011-07-16','2011-07-16','09:00:00','17:00:00','7','220','175',1,1,0,0,0,'Book Arts & Artists\' Books: A Workshop Series','Part of <a href=\"http://alanis.simmons.edu/ceweb/bookarts.php\">Book Arts & Artists Books: A Workshop Series</a>'),(55,'Instructional Design: Creating Effective Materials for Online Learning','<p>What is instructional design and why is it important in the development of online learning materials? And what is the role of instructional technology in the design process? Technology tools abound. Wikis, blogs, podcasts, asynchronous and synchronous forums have become popular and are tempting instructors to say, \"We need to develop a wiki,\" or \"We need to be podcasting,\" rather than purposefully looking at the instructional need first.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At the end of this course, you will have a basic understanding of instructional design principles as they pertain to online learning. You will be able to apply instructional design principles to solve online instructional challenges. You will also identify the role technologies play in the design process and how to determine which tool works best for what purpose, but most importantly, you will develop skills essential to preparing an online course or online tutorial.</p>','online','2011-07-01','2011-07-31','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',0,1,0,0,0,'User Instruction/Information Literacy',''),(56,'Drug Information Rx: Sources and Strategies','<p>In this workshop we will learn strategies and techniques for finding, selecting, and using the best resources to answer drug questions, whether you work in a public, special, medical, or academic library setting. Topics include an overview of the drug information landscape, including prescriptions, over-the-counter, natural medicines, and drug trials; methods for demystifying the drug information questions you may encounter; identifying the best source to answer those questions; and exposure to and practice with core print and freely available Web resources.</p>','online','2011-05-01','2011-05-31','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',1,1,0,0,0,'Reference/Research',''),(57,'Metrics for Special Collections: An Introduction','<p>What is the difference between an output and an outcome? What do granting agencies mean by demonstrating effective change through evaluation? How can we foster and embed a culture of assessment in our repositories, regardless of the types of collections we hold or number of staff? And what kind of data should we be trying to capture anyway?</p>\r\n \r\n<p>OCLCâ€™s recently released report, Taking Our Pulse: The OCLC Research Survey of Special Collections and Archives (October 2010), has the development of metrics to enable the â€œstandardized measurement of key aspects of special collections use and managementâ€ as one of its main recommendations for action. This half-day workshop is designed to introduce participants to the national metrics conversation: why archivists need to think beyond user statistics; how assessment can improve practice; and the value of metrics not only as a reporting mechanism for management, but as a way to advocate for staff and dynamically change workflow and patron interaction.</p>\r\n \r\n<p>At the end of this course, you will understand key metrics-related terminology and avenues for evaluation, and discover what tools and models are available to archivists to facilitate data collection, including MD, a tool for capturing processing metrics for archival and manuscript collections developed by Emily Gustainis.</p>','simmons','2011-06-25','2011-06-25','09:00:00','12:30:00','3.5','80','62',1,1,0,0,0,'Archives','Please note special pricing above.'),(58,'Starting and Growing a Research Business','<p style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Description</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Workforce reductions, downsizing, and layoffs are terms librarians and information professionals are all too familiar with today. For those considering a career change, itâ€™s important to realize that your knowledge base is transferrable. Developing a research business, also known as information brokering, is an exciting avenue to pursue and makes use of your existing research, writing, and communication skills. While challenging, itâ€™s never dull. Owning a research business is one way to generate income creatively, puts you in charge of your life, makes it possible to work from home, and is intellectually stimulating. You have an opportunity to meet new people across the globe and work on interesting projects that contribute to the success of your clients.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Those who operate research businesses are part of a cadre of independent information professionals (IIPs) who conduct online, telephone or library research. More specifically, you can conduct secondary and primary research or focus on competitive and market intelligence and analysis, or company and industry research. Some IIPs offer other services such as consulting, publishing, editing, or database and taxonomy development depending on interests and background.  You can work as a generalist or specialize because of many target markets, industry sectors, and niches; or, you can focus on small and large companies â€“ or both â€“ in the public or private sector.  This workshop focuses on all the basics needed to get started and answers questions such as:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What skills are required to operate a research business?</li>\r\n<li>What personality traits do I need?</li>\r\n<li>How do I market a research business and to who?</li>\r\n<li>What kinds of deliverables are expected?</li>\r\n<li>How do I establish budgets and fees?</li>\r\n<li>What are the tools of the trade and best sources for research?</li>\r\n<li>How can I gain access cost-effectively?</li>\r\n<li>What are some tips and tricks for making me a top-notch researcher?</li>\r\n<li>Where can I get more training?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Expectations</p>\r\n \r\n<p>Participants will be given weekly assignments to submit for class discussion.  Regular participation in class discussion is requested for best results in creating a high-quality synergistic learning environment for all participants.</p>','online','2011-05-01','2011-05-31','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',1,1,0,0,1,'Careers','See <a href=\"http://alanis.simmons.edu/ceweb/workshop?id=80\">additional session</a> in November.'),(59,'Periodical/Database Indexing','<p>Ever wanted to know more about indexing magazines, journals, newsletters, or newspapers?  Have you wondered how databases index periodicals? This online workshop will provide a comprehensive introduction to periodical/database indexing including the basic principles of indexing all types of periodicals, how to develop a small controlled vocabulary appropriate for the issues of a single journal title, as well as the similarities and differences in indexing for a database. Also included will be some suggestions on ways to get started in periodical/database indexing.</p>','online','2011-05-03','2011-06-13','00:00:00','00:00:00','25','275','220',0,1,0,0,1,'Information Organization',''),(60,'Please Take This Survey! An Introduction to Survey Design','<p>Surveys are a popular way to gather information from a group of people about trends, practices, opinions, and preferences.  Surveys are so popular, in fact, that there may be several vying for you attention right now!  Is that another survey in your email inbox?  How will you decide whether to answer or delete it? Does the survey appear to be relevant to you, interesting, and, perhaps most importantly, easy to complete?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Good survey design may make all the difference between a survey that is skipped and one that is completed.  In this online workshop you will learn to design an effective, easy to complete survey that provides reliable, usable results. In addition, youâ€™ll have the chance to create a survey of your own and get feedback on how to improve it. This workshop will cover:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The elements of a survey</li>\r\n<li>Survey question formats and response options</li>\r\n<li>Developing scales</li>\r\n<li>Drafting and testing a survey questionnaire</li>\r\n<li>Survey samples and response rates</li>\r\n<li>Ethical considerations</li>\r\n<li>Organizing and presenting your results</li>\r\n</ul>','online','2011-06-01','2011-06-30','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',1,1,0,0,0,'Management',''),(61,'Extending Mobile Library Services with QR Codes','<p>Are you looking to extend and develop your library\'s mobile services? QR codes offer many easily implementable and affordable opportunities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This workshop will examine:</p>\r\n \r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The basics of QR codes - what are they and how they work</li>\r\n<li>How QR codes are being used around the world to link together people, knowledge, and physical locations</li>\r\n<li>How to build QR code applications for your library</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n \r\n<p>Workshop participants will leave the course with a solid understanding of the basics and mechanics of QR codes and 20 easy ways to implement QR codes in their libraries and/or communities. All Course participants will select and complete a simple QR code course project which will give them practical experience working with QR codes.</p>','online','2011-08-01','2011-08-31','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',0,1,0,0,0,'Technology/Web 2.0',''),(80,'Starting and Growing a Research Business','<p style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Description</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Workforce reductions, downsizing, and layoffs are terms librarians and information professionals are all too familiar with today. For those considering a career change, itâ€™s important to realize that your knowledge base is transferrable. Developing a research business, also known as information brokering, is an exciting avenue to pursue and makes use of your existing research, writing, and communication skills. While challenging, itâ€™s never dull. Owning a research business is one way to generate income creatively, puts you in charge of your life, makes it possible to work from home, and is intellectually stimulating. You have an opportunity to meet new people across the globe and work on interesting projects that contribute to the success of your clients.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Those who operate research businesses are part of a cadre of independent information professionals (IIPs) who conduct online, telephone or library research. More specifically, you can conduct secondary and primary research or focus on competitive and market intelligence and analysis, or company and industry research. Some IIPs offer other services such as consulting, publishing, editing, or database and taxonomy development depending on interests and background.  You can work as a generalist or specialize because of many target markets, industry sectors, and niches; or, you can focus on small and large companies â€“ or both â€“ in the public or private sector.  This workshop focuses on all the basics needed to get started and answers questions such as:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What skills are required to operate a research business?</li>\r\n<li>What personality traits do I need?</li>\r\n<li>How do I market a research business and to who?</li>\r\n<li>What kinds of deliverables are expected?</li>\r\n<li>How do I establish budgets and fees?</li>\r\n<li>What are the tools of the trade and best sources for research?</li>\r\n<li>How can I gain access cost-effectively?</li>\r\n<li>What are some tips and tricks for making me a top-notch researcher?</li>\r\n<li>Where can I get more training?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Expectations</p>\r\n \r\n<p>Participants will be given weekly assignments to submit for class discussion.  Regular participation in class discussion is requested for best results in creating a high-quality synergistic learning environment for all participants.</p>','online','2011-11-01','2011-11-30','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',0,1,0,0,0,'Careers',''),(63,'Taxonomies and Controlled Vocabularies','<p><a href=\"http://www.hedden-information.com/GSLIS-taxonomies.htm\">Preview this workshop.</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Taxonomies are becoming popular for organizing information in business knowledge management, enterprise content management systems, and intranets. Are these taxonomies different from literature retrieval thesauri? How does one go about creating a taxonomy? This online workshop will provide recommended best practices for how to create terms, relationships, and variants for different kinds of taxonomies or controlled vocabularies, and will also introduce different software tools for doing so. Whether you need to create a taxonomy to organize information on a web site, classify information in a content management system, establish a controlled vocabulary for a periodical or database indexing project, or simply understand how to use them better, this workshop will get you on your way.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Students are expected to try out at least one demo version of thesaurus management software. Software is available for Windows, Mac (OS X 10.5 or later), and over the Web (any platform).</p>','online','2011-11-01','2011-11-30','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',0,1,0,0,0,'Information Organization',''),(70,'Presentation 2.0: Moving Beyond Powerpoint','<p>A new crop of presentation tools has emerged, each with its own benefits. This workshop will explore the use of web-based presentation tools in curriculum-driven projects with K-12 students. Among these tools are:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Voki: create personalized speaking avatars</li>\r\n<li>Voicethread: record audio over images; collaborative</li>\r\n<li>Prezi: non-linear web presentations</li>\r\n<li>Glogster: digital posters; we will add a recorded voice component using Audacity.\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>We will spend the first three weeks of class becoming familiar with these tools. The fourth and final week will be devoted to designing sample lesson plans based around a tool of each student\'s choosing.</p>','online','2011-06-01','2011-06-30','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',1,1,0,0,0,'Children\'s/YA/School Librarianship',''),(64,'Zotero','<p><a href=\"http://zotero.org/\">Zotero</a> is a free, open-source reference manager for librarians and researchers of any level, from high school student through university faculty. It takes advantage of the best features of both desktop and cloud applications to turn the Firefox web browser into a powerful research tool. In this course, an experienced instructor will take you from zero Zotero knowledge to Zotero master.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Through hands-on activities, reading, and discussion, participants in this course will:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Week 1: Install, learn, and use Zotero. Create your personal library and explore how it works. Create bibliographies for word processors or the web. Discuss how your students or users might benefit from Zotero.</li>\r\n<li>Week 2: Store your Zotero library in the cloud to access it from any computer. Use group libraries to collaborate, share, and publish resources.</li>\r\n<li>Week 3: Examine and discuss best practices for teaching and supporting Zotero in the library.</li>\r\n<li>Week 4: Learn and discuss tips, tricks, hacks, and advanced techniques. Share your final project: create a practical application for teaching or using Zotero in your own library.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Prerequisites: Participants must use the <a href=\"http://www.mozilla.com/en-US/firefox/personal.html\">Firefox web browser</a> and either Microsoft Word or Open Office. No technical skills beyond basic computer literacy are assumed.</p>','online','2011-07-01','2011-07-31','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',0,1,0,0,0,'Reference/Research',''),(65,'Practical Origami','<p>Participants will learn to transform simple sheets of paper into a variety of books, envelopes, folders, boxes and other useful objects through the art of paperfolding. Using a simple set of tools, we will manipulate paper (with the occasional cut & and rarely adhesive) into elegantly simple and dynamically functional objects. Participants will have the opportunity to work with many different papers as well as less conventional materials such as TyvekÂ®. Required tools: bone folder, utility knife, 12\" steel ruler, 12 x 18\" self-healing cutting mat, & pencil.</p>','simmons','2011-08-06','2011-08-06','09:00:00','17:00:00','7','220','175',1,1,0,0,0,'Book Arts & Artists\' Books: A Workshop Series','Part of <a href=\"http://alanis.simmons.edu/ceweb/bookarts.php\">Book Arts & Artists Books: A Workshop Series</a>'),(66,'Graphic Novels 101 for Young Readers and Schools','<p>If you\'re starting a graphic novel collection for young readers (ages 0-12) or in a school setting and want to solidify your understanding of this popular format, this online course will illuminate the joys and challenges of collecting graphic novels and comics.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Over the month national graphic novel expert Robin Brenner will start by covering all of the basics of the format: what defines graphic novels, the history of comics and graphic novels, who they\'re written for, and how to select them for your collection.  This course will cover the specific literacy graphic novels require and give all students a chance to read and discuss a selection of graphic novels for our youngest readers up to high school.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In this course we\'ll be focusing on titles for kids and within a school setting, including the range of titles for the youngest readers, how to integrate graphic novels into a school library, and how to use graphic novels wisely in the curriculum.  On top of this basic knowledge, students will have a chance to read about and discuss lesson plans and programs for kids, challenges, and cataloging related to graphic novels.  Every student should finish the month with an understanding of the format and how to start and/or maintain a collection for kids and students.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The online format encourages open discussion between students and teacher in discussing readings from both articles and graphic novels themselves, and weekly live chat sessions will be available for anyone who enjoys live discussion.  Everyone interested in this course should have access to a personal computer and the Internet and be able to navigate message boards, participate in chat sessions, and play mp3 files.</p>','online','2011-07-01','2011-07-31','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',0,1,0,0,0,'Children\'s/YA/School Librarianship',''),(67,'Author-Librarians: Using Your Work Experience to Inform Your Writing for Children & Young Adults','<p>Is there a childrenâ€™s book you have always wanted to write? Do you have a young adult novel that you\'ve started and stopped over the years? In this workshop you will take the time to focus on your writing and kickstart your project. We will use our expertise about children\'s literature to identify the best models of writing for young people, and analyze them for how they work. We will take what we learn and apply it to our own writing. We will do writing exercises specific to our lives in libraries. We will also share and critique our work. Each participant will leave with a short piece that may be a complete story, or the beginning of something longer.</p>','online','2011-06-01','2011-06-30','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',1,1,0,0,0,'Children\'s/YA/School Librarianship',''),(68,'Building a School Media Center Web Site','<p>This workshop will explore the characteristics of good web page design for the school media center. Participants will read works by authoritative writers in web design and work together to generate lists of the qualities of a good web site as well as its components. The student will learn to use web page design resources on the Internet to create a fully functional media center web site by the end of the workshop that addresses the media specialist\'s specific communication needs: using the library web site to support teacher-designed units, introduce new acquisitions to the school community, provide links to local, regional, national, and world library web sites, and offer guidance on documentation of web resources when used in research projects. Other topics for reading and discussion will include accessibility issues for web pages and image modification for use on the Internet.  The course does not require the purchase of any software to complete the assignments.</p>','online','2011-07-01','2011-07-31','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',1,1,0,0,0,'Children\'s/YA/School Librarianship',''),(69,'School Media Center 2.0','<p>This workshop will explore the ever-expanding field of interactive resources and media on the Internet and how these Web 2.0 tools can be used to enhance communication between the media center and its various patrons, as well as make the media center a 24/7 source of information, reviews, resource links, and teacher-initiated projects. Workshop participants will explore blogs, wikis, Audacity or Audioboo (creating online audio files for an audience), and a choice from among Prezi, Camtasia, and Jing (creating online video presentations). Each of these tools facilitates communication between individuals and groups. The librarian/media specialist can use all of them to communicate with the various patrons of the media center as well as to teach students and faculty how to use the same tools to explore and celebrate the resources of the library/media center. The student will create a final project using one of these Web 2.0 tools to create a themed resource with librarian-selected objectives.</p>','online','2011-08-01','2011-08-31','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',1,1,0,0,0,'Children\'s/YA/School Librarianship',''),(71,'Blogging Across the Curriculum','<p>Blogging is a versatile and skill-rich activity that can be undertaken in any discipline with any age group, from kindergarten all the way up to high school seniors. This course will explore different forms of blogging and examine how it can be used to build students\' literacy skills. In week one, we will explore different blogs and discuss them, taking special note of writing style, audience, and scope. In week two, we will create our own blogs, using Wordpress, and experiment with writing in them. We will also take this time to comment on each other\'s blogs, discuss online safety for students, and the etiquette of sharing. In week three, we will look at lesson plans that incorporate blogging into the curriculum. Finally, in week four, we will each design our own lesson plans, with a specific age group and discipline in mind.</p>','online','2011-08-01','2011-08-31','00:00:00','00:00:00','15','250','200',1,1,0,0,0,'Children\'s/YA/School Librarianship',''),(72,'Encoding and Transforming Text with Innovative Technologies','<p>This full-day workshop will introduce you to Text Encoding Initiative (TEI), an international and interdisciplinary standard for encoding and analyzing the textual content & structure of digital text.  A lecture and hands-on approach will be used to give you an overview of TEI-conformable XML markup language and CSS and XSLT stylesheets. We will use current TEI projects developed in libraries and academics to illustrate concepts and main points.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Topics will include the basic syntax of TEI-conformable XML, differences between XML and HTML, relationships between XML and other markup languages, such as SGML, EAD, and MARC XML, and Roma â€“ a TEI schema customization tool.  Through hands-on encoding a book excerpt with images, you will learn how to encode a TEI header and text by following the TEI Guidelines; and how to use the TEI Roma tool to customize a schema for validating your TEI encoded document.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We will also examine the basic syntax, structure and function of Cascading Style Sheets (CSS) and eXtensible Stylesheet Language Transformation (XSLT), explaining how the two different kinds of stylesheets work behind the scene in displaying and transforming the TEI encoded documents.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Through step-by-step exercises students will learn how to design a CSS stylesheet to display a TEI document through the Web browser, and how to design an XSLT stylesheet to transform the same TEI document into an XHTML file and display it on the Web.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>By the end of the course students will not only gain a better understanding of the practical use of TEI standard and the power of CSS and XSLT transformation, but also learn how to encode basic TEI documents and design simple stylesheets to display them.  Participants will not be expected to have any prior knowledge of XML, TEI or CSS and XSLT; however, a familiarity with HTML would be useful.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We will use Oxygen, an XML editor, to create, edit, display and transform text.</p>','simmons','2011-10-29','2011-10-29','09:30:00','17:30:00','7','220','175',1,1,0,0,0,'Technology/Web 2.0','');
